 |DirectedBy      = Nicolas Picard-Dreyfuss\n |OriginalAirDate = 2019\n |ShortSummary    = &nbsp;\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n{{Episode list\n |EpisodeNumber  = 27\n |Title           = {{lang|fr|Un Cadavre au Petit D\u00e9jeuner}}\n |Aux1            = not adapted\n |DirectedBy      = Nicolas Picard-Dreyfuss\n |OriginalAirDate = 2019/2020\n |ShortSummary    = Original musical-comedy episode;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sbs.com.au/ondemand/video/1676468291833/agatha-christies-criminal-games-a-body-with-breakfast|title=Agatha Christie's Criminal Games: A Body with Breakfast|last=|first=|date=|website=SBS On Demand|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> first aired in Italy in 2019, Australia in 2020, and in France expected late 2020)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mondofox.it/guida-tv/foxcrime/2019-10-31/|title=GUIDA TV di FoxCrime di gioved\u00ec 31 ottobre 2019|last=|first=|date=31 October 2019|website=MondoFox|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=14 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Citation|title=\"Les petits meurtres d'Agatha Christie\" Un cadavre au petit d\u00e9jeuner (TV Episode 2019) - IMDb|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt10269126/releaseinfo|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref><ref name=\"telestar\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.telestar.fr/actu-tv/exclu-telestar-les-petits-meurtres-d-agatha-christie-ce-n-est-pas-fini-467484|title=EXCLU TELESTAR. Les Petits meurtres d'Agatha Christie ce n'est... - T\u00e9l\u00e9 Star|last=Telestar.fr|date=2019-10-28|website=www.telestar.fr|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n |LineColor       = \n}}\n}}\n\n== Series Three: 1970s France (announced 2019) ==\nA third series, with a new cast and set in France in the 1970s, was announced in 2019. The first episode is expected to be released in late 2020.<ref name=\"telestar\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.programme.tv/news/series/208867-emotion-dans-greys-anatomy-la-nouvelle-saison-des-petits-meurtres-dagatha-christie-et-les-abdos-de-loup-denis-elion-les-tournages-de-la-semaine-photos/|title=Emotion dans Grey\u2019s Anatomy, la nouvelle saison des Petits Meurtres d\u2019Agatha Christie et les abdos de Loup-Denis Elion\u2026 Les tournages de la semaine (PHOTOS) - series - T\u00e9l\u00e9 2 semaines|website=www.programme.tv/news|access-date=2020-04-14}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of French television series]]\n\n==Trivia==\n* In the second season of the French TV series \"{{lang|fr|Les Petits Meurtres d'Agatha Christie}}\", Commissaire Swan Laurence drives a [[Facel Vega]] Facellia FA red Bordeaux coupe.<ref>{{cite web|title=V\u00e9hicule du film \"les petits meurtres d'Agatha Christie\"|periodical=|publisher=|url=https://www.lesanciennes.com/annonce/A312537-ventes-auto-facel-vega-facellia-fa-coupe-2-2-1960.html?ftype=&fcat=&search=FACEL%20VEGA|url-status=|format=|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=|archive-date=|last=|date=2020-03-08|year=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Facel Vega \u00e1 la T\u00e9l\u00e9vision|periodical=|publisher=|url=http://www.facel-vega.asso.fr/tv/tv.html|url-status=|format=|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=|archive-date=|last=|date=2013-03-29|year=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=RR Forums Australia|periodical=|publisher=|url=http://au.rrforums.net/forum/messages/16947/22770.html?1479246125|url-status=|format=|access-date=2020-04-09|archive-url=|archive-date=|last=|date=2016-11-15|year=|language=|pages=|quote=}}</ref>\n\n== 2006 mini-series ==\nA distinct four-part mini-series, \"{{lang|fr|Petits Meurtres en Famille}}\", adapted from ''[[Hercule Poirot's Christmas]]'', was released in 2006. Although Larosi\u00e8re and Lampion are the main characters (played by the same actors), this mini-series is not a prequel or sequel to the later series.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|id=1349600|title=Les Petits Meurtres d'Agatha Christie}}\n\n{{Television needs character section}}{{Television needs production section}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Petits Meurtres d'Agatha Christie}}\n[[Category:2009 French television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2000s French television series]]\n[[Category:2010s French television series]]\n[[Category:French crime television series]]\n[[Category:French-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Television programmes based on works by Agatha Christie]]\n", "name_user": "RLO1729", "label": "safe", "comment": "demoted Cast heading", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Les_Petits_Meurtres_d%27Agatha_Christie"}
{"title_page": "Campus of New York University", "text_new": "The [[Urban area|urban]] campus of [[New York University]] (NYU) is located in [[Manhattan]], and is around [[Washington Square Park]] in [[Greenwich Village]], and also is in [[MetroTech Center]] in [[Downtown Brooklyn]]. NYU is one of the top three largest landowners in New York City.<ref name=\"Curbed NY\" />\n\n==Washington Square campus==\n[[File:NYU Maison francaise.gif|thumb|300px|[[La Maison Fran\u00e7aise (New York University)|La Maison Fran\u00e7aise]]]]\n\nMost of NYU's buildings on the main campus are scattered across a roughly square area bounded by [[Houston Street]] to the south, [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] to the east, [[14th Street (Manhattan)|14th Street]] to the north, and [[Sixth Avenue (Manhattan)|Sixth Avenue]] (Avenue of the Americas) to the west. Most of NYU's main buildings, including the [[Silver Center]], [[Elmer Holmes Bobst Library]], [[New York University Stern School of Business|Stern School of Business]], [[Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences|Courant Institute of Mathematics]], and the [[Kimmel Center for the Performing Arts|Kimmel Center]], surround [[Gould Plaza]] and [[Washington Square Park]].\n\nSince the late 1970s, the central part of NYU is its Washington Square campus in the heart of [[Greenwich Village]]. Despite being public property, and expanding the [[Fifth Avenue]] axis into Washington Square Park, the [[Washington Square Arch]] is the unofficial symbol of NYU. Until 2008, NYU's [[Graduation|commencement]] ceremony was held in Washington Square Park. However, due to space constraints, ceremonies are now held at the [[Yankee Stadium]]. Important facilities at Washington Square are the [[Elmer Holmes Bobst Library]], designed by [[Philip Johnson]] and [[Richard Foster (architect)|Richard Foster]], who also designed several other structures, such as Tisch Hall, Meyer Hall, and the Hagop Kevorkian Center. When designing these buildings Johnson and Foster also set up a master plan for a complete redesign of the NYU Washington Square campus. However, it was never implemented. Other historic buildings include the [[Silver Center]] (formerly known as \"Main building\"); the [[Brown Building of Science]]; Judson Hall, which houses the King [[Juan Carlos I of Spain]] Center;<ref>http://www.nyu.edu/pages/kjc/flash.php</ref> Vanderbilt Hall, the historic townhouse row on [[Washington Square North]]; The Grey Art Gallery at 100 Washington Square East, housing the [[New York University]] art collection and featuring museum quality exhibitions;<ref>[http://www.nyu.edu/greyart/collection/collection.html Grey Art Gallery art collection] Retrieved March 5, 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.nyu.edu/greyart/ The Grey Art Gallery] Retrieved March 5, 2011</ref> the Kaufman Management Center; and the  Torch Club \u2013 the NYU dining and club facility for alumni, faculty, and administrators. Just a block south of Washington Square is NYU's [[Washington Square Village]], housing graduate students and junior and senior faculty residences in the Silver Towers, designed by [[I. M. Pei]], where an enlargement of Picasso's sculpture Bust of Sylvette (1934) is displayed.\n\nThe contractors of the Old University Building used prisoners from [[Sing Sing]] to cut the marble. This hiring was the catalyst for the famous [[Stonecutter's Riot]]. The old University Building was also subject to several ghost stories. It was believed that the building was haunted by a young artist resident who had died in one of the building's turrets. The spirit was said to pace through the hallways and staircases. In 1880, the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' reported that \"the structure has an evil repute with the servant girls of the neighborhood ... They have a notion that deep in subcellars lie corpses, skeletons and other dreadful things.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Q6s3AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA431|title=Ten Thousand Miles on a Bicycle|last=Bagg|first=Lyman Hotchkiss|date=1887|publisher=Karl Kron|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=431|language=en}}</ref> The [[Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire]] on March 25, 1911, took place in the Brown Building of Science (formerly the [[Asch Building]]) which today is part of the NYU campus. More than a hundred garment workers, most young women and girls, died or jumped to their deaths after a fire broke out whilst all exit doors were locked. The fire led to legislation requiring improved factory safety standards and helped spur the growth of the [[International Ladies' Garment Workers' Union]].\n\nIn the 1990s, NYU became a \"Two Square\" university by building a second community around [[Union Square, Manhattan|Union Square]], about a 10-minute walk from Washington Square. NYU's Union Square community consists of the upperclassmen residence halls of Carlyle Court, Palladium Residence Hall, University Hall, Alumni Hall, Coral Towers, Thirteenth Street Hall, and Third North Residence Hall.\n\n===NYU theaters and clubs===\nNYU operates several theaters and performance facilities that are often used by the university's [[music conservatory]] and [[Tisch School of the Arts]] but also external productions. The largest performance accommodations at NYU are the [[Skirball Center for Performing Arts]] (850 seats) at 566 LaGuardia Place, just south of Washington Square South; and the Eisner-Lubin Auditorium (560 seats) in the Kimmel Center. Recently, the Skirball Center hosted important speeches on foreign policy by [[John Kerry]]<ref>John Kerry's speech at NYU http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/iraq/2004/09/iraq-040920-kerry01.htm</ref> and [[Al Gore]]<ref>Al Gore's speech at NYU {{cite web |url=http://www.moveon.org/gore-speech.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715151552/http://www.moveon.org/gore-speech.html |archivedate=2007-07-15 }}</ref> as well as the recording of the season finale of [[The Apprentice (U.S. TV series)|The Apprentice]] 3. Well-known also is NYU's Provincetown Playhouse on MacDougal Street, where Eugene O'Neill among many others launched his career and the Frederick Loewe Theatre outside Gould Plaza. Catalyst to many careers in music (Bruce Springsteen began his career here among many others) was the famous nightclub The Bottom Line, found on the corner of West 4th and Mercer Streets. Despite the objections of many supporters, this club was evicted by NYU after being unable to meet for several months the increased rent payments.\n\n===Bobst Library===\nThe [[Elmer Holmes Bobst Library]], built between 1967 and 1972, is the largest library at NYU and one of the largest academic libraries in the U.S. Designed by [[Philip Johnson]] and [[Richard Foster (architect)|Richard Foster]], the 12-story, {{Convert|425,000|ft2|m2}} structure sits on the southern edge of Washington Square Park and is the flagship of an eight-library, 4.5 million volume system that provides students and faculty members with access to the world's scholarship and serves as a center for the University's intellectual life. Bobst Library contains more than 3.3 million volumes, 20,000 journals, and more than 3.5 million microforms. The library is visited by more than 6,500 users each day, and circulates almost one million books annually.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://afghanistandl.nyu.edu/about/library.html# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2007-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708230006/http://afghanistandl.nyu.edu/about/library.html# |archive-date=2007-07-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In addition to its regular collection it houses a number of special collections and archives, including the Archives of Irish America and the [[Tamiment Library and Robert F. Wagner Archives]].\n\nThe floor of the library, when viewed from above, was designed to appear three-dimensional. In late 2003, Bobst Library was the site of two suicidal incidents. Two students jumped from the open-air crosswalks inside the library onto the marble floor below. The students later died of their injuries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nyusuicides.com/mediaclips005.html# |title=Media Clips<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2007-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070504132957/http://www.nyusuicides.com/mediaclips005.html# |archive-date=2007-05-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After the second suicide, NYU installed plexi-glass windows on each level to prevent further attempts. In 2003, Bobst Library was also in the news for being the home of a [[Bobst Boy|homeless student]] who resided at the library because he could not afford student housing.<ref>[http://www.homelessatnyu.com/ charity age concern donation fund at homelessatnyu.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/3665885.stm Broke student 'slept in library']\n\n===Real estate and development===\nGreenwich Village has long had a mixed relationship with NYU. Residents and university leaders frequently have differing views on how the school, its buildings and its students should interact with the neighborhood.<ref name=\"Curbed NY\">{{cite web|last1=Rosenberg|first1=Eli|title=After A Long War, Can NYU and the Village Ever Make Peace?|url=http://ny.curbed.com/archives/2014/03/19/after_a_long_war_can_nyu_and_the_village_ever_make_peace.php|work=Curbed NY|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe tearing down of a block of tenements and brownstones in 1950 for construction of Vanderbilt Hall, the law school, was a signal of things to come. Residents both mourned the loss of the old block, on Washington Square South between [[MacDougal Street|MacDougal]] and [[Sullivan Street]]s, and worried about the university dominating the Washington Square area.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grabar|first1=Henry|title=A Brief History of NYU Land Battles|url=http://www.citylab.com/politics/2012/07/brief-history-nyu-land-battles/2600/|publisher=The Atlantic Citylab|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Following the closure of the Bronx campus (see History section above), the school expanded downtown, growing significantly \u2013 both in student body size and academic and dormitory footprint \u2013 from the 1980s through the present.<ref name=\"Curbed NY\"/>\n\nIn addition to the sheer mass of the school's real estate holdings, its approach to architecture has often been criticized. From 1964, when noted architecture critic [[Ada Louise Huxtable]] wrote that NYU had a \"consistent blindness to the area's architectural and historical features\",<ref>Ibid {{clarify|date=August 2017|post-text=Ibid where?}}</ref> to 2013, when critic James Russell wrote that \"for decades, New York University has waged architectural war on Greenwich Village\",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Russell|first1=James|title=NYU Blights Village With Dumpsters, Fencing, Concrete|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-12-11/nyu-blights-village-with-dumpsters-fencing-concrete.html|work=Bloomberg News|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> the school has developed a reputation for construction that is insensitive to both aesthetic and community concerns.\n\nWhile the Bobst Library, built in 1973, and the many dorms built throughout the 1980s and 1990s all had their detractors, construction of the Kimmel Center for University Life (opened 2003) on Washington Square South sparked broader attention. Critics said the building would ruin the Fifth Avenue view through the Washington Square Arch and cast a shadow on the park, issues impacting a broader swath of city residents and tourists. Over the years, a local preservation group, the [[Greenwich Village Society for Historic Preservation]] (GVSHP), has been a vocal opponent of NYU.<ref>{{cite web|title=After the Kimmel Center: How Can We Better Plan to Protect Our Neighborhoods, Parks and View Corridors?|url=http://www.gvshp.org/_gvshp/preservation/nyu/doc/after-kimmel.pdf|publisher=Greenwich Village Society for Historic Preservation|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> GVSHP was one of several dozen participants, including NYU itself, in the Community Task Force on NYU Development, which was convened by Manhattan Borough President Scott Stringer in 2006. \"In order to maintain the integrity of the affected neighborhoods, the University's goals for growth and development must be better aligned with those of the community at large\" stated the Findings and Recommendations report of March 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Community Task Force on NYU Development|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/mancb2/downloads/pdf/task_force_recommendations.1.pdf|publisher=Manhattan Borough President Scott Stringer|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Controversies in recent years include:\n\n* Edgar Allan Poe house \u2013 As the university contemplated new construction to expand its law school, preservationists called for protection of 85 West [[Third Street (Manhattan)|Third Street]], where Poe lived from 1844 through early 1846. It is where he wrote \"[[The Cask of Amontillado]]\" and revised and published \"[[The Raven]]\". They asked the Landmarks Preservation Commission to protect the building, but it did not, so they also filed suit to save it. NYU officials said they did not consider the Poe house, or the Judson House on the same block (between Sullivan and [[Thompson Street (Manhattan)|Thompson Street]]s), important enough to save.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Siegal|first1=Nina|title=Rapping on Poe's Door, A Hint of Nevermore; Anger in Village Over N.Y.U. Tower Plan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/07/19/nyregion/rapping-on-poe-s-door-a-hint-of-nevermore-anger-in-village-over-nyu-tower-plan.html?module=Search&mabReward=relbias:r,{%221=%22:=%22RI:10=%22}=&pagewanted=1|work=The New York Times|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Both were razed for construction of Furman Hall. Although NYU promised to incorporate a rebuilt Poe House into the new building, using original materials, officials eventually claimed not to have enough bricks to do so, and preservationists said the antique simulacrum revealed in 2003 did not resemble the razed building.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Denny|title=Neighborhood Report: Greenwich Village; The Poe House, and Its Mask of Red Bricks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/10/19/nyregion/neighborhood-report-greenwich-village-the-poe-house-and-its-mask-of-red-bricks.html?module=Search&mabReward=relbias%3Ar%2C{%221%22%3A%22RI%3A10%22}|work=The New York Times|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n* St. Ann's Church \u2013 An unusual-looking high-rise in the East Village \u2013 the neighborhood's tallest \u2013 is a symbol of another conflict between the school's plans and residents' desires. On the site of the demolished St. Ann's Church on East 12th Street between Third and Fourth Avenues, the university planned to build a dorm and solicited community input on its plans. The community asked that the 240-foot-tall building be scaled back, only to find in 2006 that construction plans were moving ahead to build a 26-story dormitory. That building, Founder's Hall, now towers over one preserved wall of the former St. Ann's Church, the gray stone fa\u00e7ade facing E. 12th Street.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Lincoln|title=Conceding nothing, N.Y.U. starts building megadorm|url=http://thevillager.com/villager_170/concedingnothingnyu.html|work=[[The Villager (Manhattan)|The Villager]]|accessdate=8 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820064150/http://thevillager.com/villager_170/concedingnothingnyu.html|archive-date=20 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Provincetown Playhouse and Apartments \u2013 Located at 133-139 MacDougal Street, this four-story complex hosted performances of works by playwrights from Edna St. Vincent Millay to Eugene O'Neill to Sam Shepard in its playhouse, while artists and others found shelter in the apartments above. In 2008 the school proposed to demolish the entire building and rebuild a facility for the law school, as well as a new theater.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Amateau|first1=Albert|title=N.Y.U. would drop curtain on O'Neill's playhouse|url=http://thevillager.com/villager_260/nyuwoulddrop.html|work=[[The Villager (Manhattan)|The Villager]]|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> The same year, the New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation responded positively to GVSHP's request that the building be found eligible for listing on the State and National Registers of Historic Places. In the face of community opposition, NYU agreed to preserve just six percent of the old building: the walls containing the small theater in the southern corner of the building. However, during construction, behind construction barriers and invisible from the street, NYU secretly tore down parts of the walls they promised to preserve, a fact publicly revealed by GVSHP.<ref>{{cite web|title=Re: Failure to Maintain Commitments re:Provincetown Playhouse Theater Restoration|url=http://www.gvshp.org/_gvshp/preservation/ptown/doc/ltr-nyu-11-19-10.pdf|publisher=Greenwich Village Society for Historic Preservation|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>  \n* NYU 2031 \u2013 This ambitious plan for the university's expansion was met by wide resistance both among unaffiliated city residents, and among university faculty and staff.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Berger|first1=Joseph|title=N.Y.U.'s Plan for Expansion Draws Anger in Community|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/10/nyregion/nyu-expansion-plan-upsets-some-greenwich-village-neighbors.html?pagewanted=all|work=The New York Times|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Not only did community members consider the plan itself an abrogation of the \"Planning Principles\" that came out of the Community Task Force, but a new group formed called NYU Faculty Against the Sexton Plan (NYU FASP). When the city approved the 2031 plan, FASP, GVSHP and others filed suit to stop it. In January 2014, State Supreme Court Justice Donna Mills halted the plan based on illegal takings of parkland, but NYU appealed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bagli|first1=Charles|title=Judge Blocks Part of N.Y.U.'s Plan for Four Towers in Greenwich Village|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/08/nyregion/judge-blocks-part-of-nyus-plan-for-four-towers-in-greenwich-village.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Recent construction===\nOver the last few years, NYU has developed a number of new facilities on and around its Washington Square campus.\n\nThe Kimmel Center for University Life, named for benefactors Helen and [[Martin Kimmel]], was built in 2003 to house the majority of the University's student services offices. The center also houses the Skirball Center for the Performing Arts, the Rosenthal Pavilion, the Eisner & Lubin Auditorium, and the Loeb Student Center. The Jack H. Skirball Center for the Performing Arts is a professionally operated and programmed 850-seat [[Proscenium|proscenium theater]]. Presentations there have included the Abbey Theater of Dublin's Playboy of the Western World, the world premiere of Mabou Mines Red Beads, a series of concerts by World Music Institute, and a series of superlative dance companies, including Lar Lubovitch and Bill T. Jones. The Skirball Center is the largest performing arts facility south of [[42nd Street (Manhattan)|42nd Street]].<ref>http://www.nyu.edu/kimmel/perf_arts.shtml The Skirball Center for the Performing Arts</ref>\n\nThe School of Law's Furman Hall, built in 2004, was named for NYU Law alumnus Jay Furman (JD '71). Rebuilt elements of two historic buildings were incorporated into the new facade, one of which was occupied by poet [[Edgar Allan Poe]].<ref>Albert Amateau. [http://www.thevillager.com/villager_37/nyuopensnew.html \"N.Y.U. opens new building for law school\".] ''The Villager''. Volume 73, Number 37, January 14\u20132, 2004</ref>\n\nIn 2005, NYU announced the development of a new life science facility on [[Waverly Place]]. The facility will accommodate laboratories and related academic space for the life sciences and will be the first NYU science building developed since the opening of Meyer Hall in 1971.<ref>Lincoln Anderson. \"N.Y.U. to use Waverly buildings for its new life sciences center\". ''The Villager''. Volume 74, Number 28, November 17\u201322, 2004 http://www.thevillager.com/villager_81/nyutousewaverly.html</ref>\n\nIn November 2005, NYU announced plans to build a 26-floor, {{convert|190000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} residence hall on 12th Street. The residence hall is expected to accommodate about 700 undergraduates and contain a host of other student facilities. It is to be the tallest building in the [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]].<ref>[http://media.www.nyunews.com/media/storage/paper869/news/2005/11/08/NewscampusNews/New-Dorm.Coming.In.2009-2387197.shtml New dorm coming in 2009: 26-story residence hall to be built on 12th Street] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013035314/http://media.www.nyunews.com/media/storage/paper869/news/2005/11/08/NewscampusNews/New-Dorm.Coming.In.2009-2387197.shtml# |date=2007-10-13 }}, ''NYU News'', November 8, 2005</ref> The plans have caused anger among East Village and other [[New York City]] residents, as the new building would be built over the old St. Ann's Church.<ref>[http://villagevoice.com/news/0610,lombardi,72426,2.html Not Subject to Review: As NYU plans towering dorm for 12th Street, East Village neighbors cry foul] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626080717/http://www.villagevoice.com/news/0610,lombardi,72426,2.html# |date=2007-06-26 }}, ''[[The Village Voice]]'', March 7, 2006</ref> Following construction, the new residence hall was named [[Founders Hall (New York University)|Founders Hall]].\n\nA new $1.3 billion building will replace the [[Coles Sports and Recreation Center]] at 404 Lafayette Street formerly located on the site. The building, set to open in 2021, will include a gym, a swimming pool, three theaters and class rooms. It will be topped by two towers with faculty and student housing.<ref>http://asumag.com/facility-planning/new-york-university-details-plans-13-billion-building</ref>\n\n==Brooklyn campus==\n[[File:Wunsch Building.JPG|alt=|left|thumb|Wunsch Building, a former church]]\nThe [[New York University Tandon School of Engineering|Tandon School of Engineering]] is located in [[Downtown Brooklyn]]. It is centrally located in the [[MetroTech Center]] and is close to transportation routes and easily accessible from all parts of New York City and Long Island. The Brooklyn campus offers programs for undergraduates students as well as for graduate students, including those executive programs for students with related experience.\n\nThe engineering school played a leadership role in bringing about MetroTech Center, one of the largest urban university-corporate parks in the world and the largest in the United States. Today, the 16-acre (65,000 m\u00b2), $1 billion complex is home to the institute and several technology-dependent companies, including Securities Industry Automation Corporation (SIAC), New York City Police Department's 911 Center, New York City Fire Department Headquarters and the U.S. technology and operations functions of JPMorgan Chase. In 1998, a Marriott Hotel was built adjacent to MetroTech. MetroTech has proven to be a case study in effective university, corporate, government and private-developer cooperation. It has resulted in renewing an area that once was characterized more by urban decay.\n\nThe [[Wunsch Building]] which now houses the NYU Wasserman Center for Career Development's Brooklyn Office, dates back to 1847 and was the first independent black church in Brooklyn. It was also a stop on the Underground Railroad and has been designated a historic landmark since November 24, 1981.\n\nThe Bern Dibner Library of Science and Technology, opened in 1990, is the engineering school's library.  In addition, wireless networks allow users with notebook computers to access the library's electronic services from anywhere on campus.\n\nThe Brooklyn campus also houses the [[Center for Urban Science and Progress]] as well as several of [[Tisch School of the Arts]]<ref name=\"animationcareerreview.com\">http://www.animationcareerreview.com/articles/top-50-game-design-schools-and-colleges-us-%E2%80%93-2015</ref> and [[Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development]]'s degree programs.<ref>http://magnet.nyu.edu/</ref> The Brooklyn campus houses NYU's Game Center Open Library, which is the largest collection of games held by any university in the world.<ref name=\"animationcareerreview.com\"/> In 2014, [[NYU Langone Medical Center]] acquired a 125,000 square foot healthcare facility in Brooklyn.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Frost|first1=Mary|title=NYU Langone to take over LICH emergency department in Brooklyn on Friday|url=http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2014/10/29/nyu-langone-take-over-lich-emergency-department-brooklyn-friday|website=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|accessdate=April 4, 2016|date=October 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDesign and engineering work for the full renovation and fit-out of [[370 Jay Street]] in Brooklyn is underway. Construction began in February 2015,<ref>{{cite web|title=Construction; Current Projects: 370 Jay Street|url=https://www.nyu.edu/community/nyu-in-nyc/construction/current-projects/370-Jay-Street-project.html|publisher=[[New York University]]|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref> and NYU started moving into the building in December 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.metro.us/news/local-news/new-york/nyu-moves-tech-hub-long-empty-former-mta-headquarters|title=NYU moves tech hub into long-empty former MTA headquarters|last=Toussaint|first=Kristin|date=2017-12-13|work=Metro US|access-date=2017-12-15|language=en}}</ref> The 460,000-square-foot building, which NYU acquired in 2013, is adjacent to its Tandon School of Engineering.<ref name=\"nyu.edu\"/>\n\n==Medical campus==\nThe main NYU medical campus is situated at the East River waterfront at First Ave. between East 30th and [[34th Street (Manhattan)|34th Street]]s. The campus hosts the Medical School, Tisch Hospital, and the [[Rusk Institute of Rehabilitation Medicine]]. Other NYU Centers across the city include NYU Hospital for Joint Diseases and the Bellevue Hospital Center. NYU's Ehrenkranz School of Social Work manages branch campus programs in Westchester County at [[Manhattanville College]] and in [[Rockland County]] at [[St. Thomas Aquinas College]]. In Sterling Forest, near Tuxedo, New York, NYU has a research facility that contains several institutes, in particular the Nelson Institute of Environmental Medicine. The Midtown Center at 11 West 42nd Street and the [[Woolworth Building]] in the financial district are home to NYU's continuing education programs.\n\n===Recent construction===\n* Ronald O. Perelman Center for Emergency Services, completed in 2014.<ref>http://nyulangone.org/our-story/campus-transformation/building-the-ronald-o-perelman-center-for-emergency-services</ref>\n* Energy Building, completed in 2016.<ref>http://nyulangone.org/our-story/campus-transformation/building-the-energy-building</ref>\n* 16-story Science Building, will be completed in 2017.<ref name=\"ny.curbed.com\">http://ny.curbed.com/2016/7/7/12116632/nyu-langone-expansion-kips-bay</ref>\n* 21-story Helen L. and Martin S. Kimmel Pavilion, will be completed in 2018.<ref name=\"ny.curbed.com\"/>\n\n==Foreign facilities==\nNYU has an extensive study abroad program in which a good portion of the student body participates; hence, the school has earned the nickname \"Global U\".{{Cite quote|date=August 2017}} Unlike most other universities, NYU has its own international facilities in several countries. One noteworthy example is the {{convert|57|acre|m2|adj=on}} campus of NYU Florence at [[Villa La Pietra]] in Italy, bequeathed by the late Sir [[Harold Acton]] to NYU in 1994.<ref>[http://www.nyu.edu/nyutoday/archives/16/01/Stories/LaPietra.html NYU Today<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> NYU manages undergraduate academic year study abroad programs at [[NYU Florence]], [[NYU London]], [[NYU Paris]], NYU Prague, NYU Berlin, NYU Accra, NYU Madrid, [[NYU Shanghai]], NYU Buenos Aires, NYU Tel Aviv, [[NYU Abu Dhabi]], NYU Washington, DC, and NYU Sydney.\n\n==International houses on campus==\nNYU has several international houses to foster the study of international culture and languages. The international houses have their own classroom space, libraries, offices, and often host campus events. The NYU international houses are:\n* [[Casa Italiana Zerilli-Marim\u00f2]]\n* [[La Maison Fran\u00e7aise (New York University)|La Maison Fran\u00e7aise]]\n* Deutsches Haus<ref>[http://deutscheshaus.as.nyu.edu/page/home Deutsches Haus]</ref>\n* Glucksman Ireland House<ref>[http://www.irelandhouse.fas.nyu.edu Glucksman Ireland House]</ref>\n* King Juan Carlos I of Spain Center\n* Hagop Kevorkian Center<ref>[http://neareaststudies.as.nyu.edu/page/home Hagop Kevorkian Center]</ref>\n* Africa House\n* China House\n\nNYU was also the founding member of the [[League of World Universities]].\n\n==Residence halls==\n[[File:NYU Founders Hall St. Ann's Church.jpg|thumb|right|Founder's Hall]]\n{{Main|NYU residence halls}}\nWith 12,500 residents, NYU has the seventh largest university housing system in the U.S. and the largest among private schools.<ref>[http://www.housing.umich.edu/general/topten.html UM General Information<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070305034155/http://www.housing.umich.edu/general/topten.html |date=2007-03-05 }}</ref> Uniquely, many of NYU residence halls are converted apartment complexes or old hotels. Most freshman residence halls are in the Washington Square area. While nearly all the upper classmen dorms are in the Union Square area, a few of them are as far as the [[Financial District, Manhattan]]. Until the Spring 2005 semester, NYU used a lottery system to determine eligibility for residence hall preference. Under this system, a student received one point for every semester they had lived in campus housing. Freshmen are freed from the lottery system and are by tradition placed in the halls closest to the main campus area. Therefore, historically, most of the students who lived in dorms found off-campus were sophomores. However, beginning in the fall 2006 semester, sophomores received priority housing, giving them first choice of residence halls. The purpose of this initiative was to keep the sophomore class together in the [[Union Square, Manhattan|Union Square]] area. As a result, the junior class (class of 2008) and the senior class (class of 2007) never benefited from first choice as sophomores or seniors. The university operates its own transit system to transport its students, by bus or trolley, to campus. Undergraduate students are guaranteed housing during their enrollment at NYU.\n\nTwenty-two buildings are in NYU's undergraduate housing system in the United States. In general, NYU residence halls receive favorable ratings, and some are opulent. Many rooms are spacious and contain amenities considered rare for individual college residence hall rooms, such as kitchens and living rooms/common areas, one residence hall even has maid service. All residence halls are staffed by 24-hour security staff, contain multiple [[resident assistant]]s (RAs), and several halls contain faculty in residence. Unlike many other universities, NYU rooms all have their own bathrooms and thus no common bathrooms exist. Many residence halls have their own dining hall, and the university has meal choices to suit various diets. Almost all the residence halls have a [[laundry]] room that is open to resident students 24 hours a day.\n\nAll the residence halls are governed by the [[Residence hall association|Inter-Residence Hall Council]] (IRHC), an umbrella student council organization. Each hall elects student representatives to the IRHC, and those representatives meet with one another to form committees and vote on an executive board. The goal of this group is to create programs for university students and to act as a link to university administration. [[Hometalk]] ranked NYU's student residences third in the United States in its list of best college dorms.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hometalk.com/6444015/most-impressive-dorms |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-04-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504063304/http://www.hometalk.com/6444015/most-impressive-dorms |archive-date=2016-05-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Recent acquisitions==\nSome of the recent acquisitions include, among others:\n\n*In 2010, NYU purchased a 125,000 square foot building. Full renovation of 60 [[Fifth Avenue]] (formerly the Forbes Building) is expected to commence in February 2015.<ref name=\"nyu.edu\">http://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/budget/capital-budget.html</ref> \n*In 2014, NYU bought a 151,000-square-foot building in [[NoHo, Manhattan]] for $157 million and renovated it.<ref>http://therealdeal.com/blog/2014/10/28/nyu-buys-noho-building-for-157m/</ref> \n*In 2014, NYU acquired a 125,000 square foot healthcare facility in [[Brooklyn]].<ref>http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2014/10/29/nyu-langone-take-over-lich-emergency-department-brooklyn-friday</ref>\n*In 2016, NYU bought a 94-unit rental building near Gramercy Park for $87.5 million. NYU purchased the building on behalf of its NYU School of Medicine to \"provide housing primarily for trainees and staff, including house staff, post-docs, and researchers. NYU Langone Medical Center's Tisch Hospital is located a few blocks north of the property, with other NYU medical facilities also located nearby on Manhattan's East Side\".<ref>http://therealdeal.com/2016/03/08/nyu-acquires-gramercy-park-rental-from-benchmark-for-88m/</ref>\n*In 2016, NYU signed a 30-year agreement to take 390,000 square feet of space at 222 East 41st, including all 25 floors, the lobby, common areas and the parking garage.<ref>http://therealdeal.com/2016/04/28/nyu-langone-leases-entire-390k-sf-building-in-midtown-east/</ref>\n*In 2016, NYU acquired [[Winthrop University Hospital]].<ref>http://libn.com/2016/09/29/nyu-langone-winthrop-approve-merger/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Ibid|date=March 2020}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{New York University}}\n\n{{Coord|40|43|46|N|73|59|47|W|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:New York University|Campus]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Manhattan|New York University Campus]]\n[[Category:Culture of Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Greenwich Village|New York University Campus]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Manhattan|New York University Campus]]\n", "text_old": "The [[Urban area|urban]] campus of [[New York University]] (NYU) is located in [[Manhattan]], and is around [[Washington Square Park]] in [[Greenwich Village]], and also is in [[MetroTech Center]] in [[Downtown Brooklyn]]. NYU is one of the top three largest landowners in New York City.<ref name=\"Curbed NY\" />\n\n==Washington Square campus==\n[[File:NYU Maison francaise.gif|thumb|300px|[[La Maison Fran\u00e7aise (New York University)|La Maison Fran\u00e7aise]]]]\n\nMost of NYU's buildings on the main campus are scattered across a roughly square area bounded by [[Houston Street]] to the south, [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] to the east, [[14th Street (Manhattan)|14th Street]] to the north, and [[Sixth Avenue (Manhattan)|Sixth Avenue]] (Avenue of the Americas) to the west. Most of NYU's main buildings, including the [[Silver Center]], [[Elmer Holmes Bobst Library]], and the [[Kimmel Center for the Performing Arts|Kimmel Center]], surround [[Washington Square Park]].\n\nSince the late 1970s, the central part of NYU is its Washington Square campus in the heart of [[Greenwich Village]]. Despite being public property, and expanding the [[Fifth Avenue]] axis into Washington Square Park, the [[Washington Square Arch]] is the unofficial symbol of NYU. Until 2008, NYU's [[Graduation|commencement]] ceremony was held in Washington Square Park. However, due to space constraints, ceremonies are now held at the [[Yankee Stadium]]. Important facilities at Washington Square are the [[Elmer Holmes Bobst Library]], designed by [[Philip Johnson]] and [[Richard Foster (architect)|Richard Foster]], who also designed several other structures, such as Tisch Hall, Meyer Hall, and the Hagop Kevorkian Center. When designing these buildings Johnson and Foster also set up a master plan for a complete redesign of the NYU Washington Square campus. However, it was never implemented. Other historic buildings include the [[Silver Center]] (formerly known as \"Main building\"); the [[Brown Building of Science]]; Judson Hall, which houses the King [[Juan Carlos I of Spain]] Center;<ref>http://www.nyu.edu/pages/kjc/flash.php</ref> Vanderbilt Hall, the historic townhouse row on [[Washington Square North]]; The Grey Art Gallery at 100 Washington Square East, housing the [[New York University]] art collection and featuring museum quality exhibitions;<ref>[http://www.nyu.edu/greyart/collection/collection.html Grey Art Gallery art collection] Retrieved March 5, 2011</ref><ref>[http://www.nyu.edu/greyart/ The Grey Art Gallery] Retrieved March 5, 2011</ref> the Kaufman Management Center; and the  Torch Club \u2013 the NYU dining and club facility for alumni, faculty, and administrators. Just a block south of Washington Square is NYU's [[Washington Square Village]], housing graduate students and junior and senior faculty residences in the Silver Towers, designed by [[I. M. Pei]], where an enlargement of Picasso's sculpture Bust of Sylvette (1934) is displayed.\n\nThe contractors of the Old University Building used prisoners from [[Sing Sing]] to cut the marble. This hiring was the catalyst for the famous [[Stonecutter's Riot]]. The old University Building was also subject to several ghost stories. It was believed that the building was haunted by a young artist resident who had died in one of the building's turrets. The spirit was said to pace through the hallways and staircases. In 1880, the ''[[San Francisco Chronicle]]'' reported that \"the structure has an evil repute with the servant girls of the neighborhood ... They have a notion that deep in subcellars lie corpses, skeletons and other dreadful things.\"<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Q6s3AAAAMAAJ&pg=PA431|title=Ten Thousand Miles on a Bicycle|last=Bagg|first=Lyman Hotchkiss|date=1887|publisher=Karl Kron|year=|isbn=|location=|pages=431|language=en}}</ref> The [[Triangle Shirtwaist Factory fire]] on March 25, 1911, took place in the Brown Building of Science (formerly the [[Asch Building]]) which today is part of the NYU campus. More than a hundred garment workers, most young women and girls, died or jumped to their deaths after a fire broke out whilst all exit doors were locked. The fire led to legislation requiring improved factory safety standards and helped spur the growth of the [[International Ladies' Garment Workers' Union]].\n\nIn the 1990s, NYU became a \"Two Square\" university by building a second community around [[Union Square, Manhattan|Union Square]], about a 10-minute walk from Washington Square. NYU's Union Square community consists of the upperclassmen residence halls of Carlyle Court, Palladium Residence Hall, University Hall, Alumni Hall, Coral Towers, Thirteenth Street Hall, and Third North Residence Hall.\n\n===NYU theaters and clubs===\nNYU operates several theaters and performance facilities that are often used by the university's [[music conservatory]] and [[Tisch School of the Arts]] but also external productions. The largest performance accommodations at NYU are the [[Skirball Center for Performing Arts]] (850 seats) at 566 LaGuardia Place, just south of Washington Square South; and the Eisner-Lubin Auditorium (560 seats) in the Kimmel Center. Recently, the Skirball Center hosted important speeches on foreign policy by [[John Kerry]]<ref>John Kerry's speech at NYU http://www.globalsecurity.org/wmd/library/news/iraq/2004/09/iraq-040920-kerry01.htm</ref> and [[Al Gore]]<ref>Al Gore's speech at NYU {{cite web |url=http://www.moveon.org/gore-speech.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2007-07-15 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070715151552/http://www.moveon.org/gore-speech.html |archivedate=2007-07-15 }}</ref> as well as the recording of the season finale of [[The Apprentice (U.S. TV series)|The Apprentice]] 3. Well-known also is NYU's Provincetown Playhouse on MacDougal Street, where Eugene O'Neill among many others launched his career and the Frederick Loewe Theatre. Catalyst to many careers in music (Bruce Springsteen began his career here among many others) was the famous nightclub The Bottom Line, found on the corner of West 4th and Mercer Streets. Despite the objections of many supporters, this club was evicted by NYU after being unable to meet for several months the increased rent payments.\n\n===Bobst Library===\nThe [[Elmer Holmes Bobst Library]], built between 1967 and 1972, is the largest library at NYU and one of the largest academic libraries in the U.S. Designed by [[Philip Johnson]] and [[Richard Foster (architect)|Richard Foster]], the 12-story, {{Convert|425,000|ft2|m2}} structure sits on the southern edge of Washington Square Park and is the flagship of an eight-library, 4.5 million volume system that provides students and faculty members with access to the world's scholarship and serves as a center for the University's intellectual life. Bobst Library contains more than 3.3 million volumes, 20,000 journals, and more than 3.5 million microforms. The library is visited by more than 6,500 users each day, and circulates almost one million books annually.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://afghanistandl.nyu.edu/about/library.html# |title=Archived copy |access-date=2007-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070708230006/http://afghanistandl.nyu.edu/about/library.html# |archive-date=2007-07-08 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In addition to its regular collection it houses a number of special collections and archives, including the Archives of Irish America and the [[Tamiment Library and Robert F. Wagner Archives]].\n\nThe floor of the library, when viewed from above, was designed to appear three-dimensional. In late 2003, Bobst Library was the site of two suicidal incidents. Two students jumped from the open-air crosswalks inside the library onto the marble floor below. The students later died of their injuries.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nyusuicides.com/mediaclips005.html# |title=Media Clips<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=2007-05-09 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070504132957/http://www.nyusuicides.com/mediaclips005.html# |archive-date=2007-05-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After the second suicide, NYU installed plexi-glass windows on each level to prevent further attempts. In 2003, Bobst Library was also in the news for being the home of a [[Bobst Boy|homeless student]] who resided at the library because he could not afford student housing.<ref>[http://www.homelessatnyu.com/ charity age concern donation fund at homelessatnyu.com<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> [http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/education/3665885.stm Broke student 'slept in library']\n\n===Real estate and development===\nGreenwich Village has long had a mixed relationship with NYU. Residents and university leaders frequently have differing views on how the school, its buildings and its students should interact with the neighborhood.<ref name=\"Curbed NY\">{{cite web|last1=Rosenberg|first1=Eli|title=After A Long War, Can NYU and the Village Ever Make Peace?|url=http://ny.curbed.com/archives/2014/03/19/after_a_long_war_can_nyu_and_the_village_ever_make_peace.php|work=Curbed NY|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nThe tearing down of a block of tenements and brownstones in 1950 for construction of Vanderbilt Hall, the law school, was a signal of things to come. Residents both mourned the loss of the old block, on Washington Square South between [[MacDougal Street|MacDougal]] and [[Sullivan Street]]s, and worried about the university dominating the Washington Square area.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Grabar|first1=Henry|title=A Brief History of NYU Land Battles|url=http://www.citylab.com/politics/2012/07/brief-history-nyu-land-battles/2600/|publisher=The Atlantic Citylab|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Following the closure of the Bronx campus (see History section above), the school expanded downtown, growing significantly \u2013 both in student body size and academic and dormitory footprint \u2013 from the 1980s through the present.<ref name=\"Curbed NY\"/>\n\nIn addition to the sheer mass of the school's real estate holdings, its approach to architecture has often been criticized. From 1964, when noted architecture critic [[Ada Louise Huxtable]] wrote that NYU had a \"consistent blindness to the area's architectural and historical features\",<ref>Ibid {{clarify|date=August 2017|post-text=Ibid where?}}</ref> to 2013, when critic James Russell wrote that \"for decades, New York University has waged architectural war on Greenwich Village\",<ref>{{cite web|last1=Russell|first1=James|title=NYU Blights Village With Dumpsters, Fencing, Concrete|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-12-11/nyu-blights-village-with-dumpsters-fencing-concrete.html|work=Bloomberg News|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> the school has developed a reputation for construction that is insensitive to both aesthetic and community concerns.\n\nWhile the Bobst Library, built in 1973, and the many dorms built throughout the 1980s and 1990s all had their detractors, construction of the Kimmel Center for University Life (opened 2003) on Washington Square South sparked broader attention. Critics said the building would ruin the Fifth Avenue view through the Washington Square Arch and cast a shadow on the park, issues impacting a broader swath of city residents and tourists. Over the years, a local preservation group, the [[Greenwich Village Society for Historic Preservation]] (GVSHP), has been a vocal opponent of NYU.<ref>{{cite web|title=After the Kimmel Center: How Can We Better Plan to Protect Our Neighborhoods, Parks and View Corridors?|url=http://www.gvshp.org/_gvshp/preservation/nyu/doc/after-kimmel.pdf|publisher=Greenwich Village Society for Historic Preservation|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> GVSHP was one of several dozen participants, including NYU itself, in the Community Task Force on NYU Development, which was convened by Manhattan Borough President Scott Stringer in 2006. \"In order to maintain the integrity of the affected neighborhoods, the University's goals for growth and development must be better aligned with those of the community at large\" stated the Findings and Recommendations report of March 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Community Task Force on NYU Development|url=http://www.nyc.gov/html/mancb2/downloads/pdf/task_force_recommendations.1.pdf|publisher=Manhattan Borough President Scott Stringer|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Controversies in recent years include:\n\n* Edgar Allan Poe house \u2013 As the university contemplated new construction to expand its law school, preservationists called for protection of 85 West [[Third Street (Manhattan)|Third Street]], where Poe lived from 1844 through early 1846. It is where he wrote \"[[The Cask of Amontillado]]\" and revised and published \"[[The Raven]]\". They asked the Landmarks Preservation Commission to protect the building, but it did not, so they also filed suit to save it. NYU officials said they did not consider the Poe house, or the Judson House on the same block (between Sullivan and [[Thompson Street (Manhattan)|Thompson Street]]s), important enough to save.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Siegal|first1=Nina|title=Rapping on Poe's Door, A Hint of Nevermore; Anger in Village Over N.Y.U. Tower Plan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/07/19/nyregion/rapping-on-poe-s-door-a-hint-of-nevermore-anger-in-village-over-nyu-tower-plan.html?module=Search&mabReward=relbias:r,{%221=%22:=%22RI:10=%22}=&pagewanted=1|work=The New York Times|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Both were razed for construction of Furman Hall. Although NYU promised to incorporate a rebuilt Poe House into the new building, using original materials, officials eventually claimed not to have enough bricks to do so, and preservationists said the antique simulacrum revealed in 2003 did not resemble the razed building.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Denny|title=Neighborhood Report: Greenwich Village; The Poe House, and Its Mask of Red Bricks|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/10/19/nyregion/neighborhood-report-greenwich-village-the-poe-house-and-its-mask-of-red-bricks.html?module=Search&mabReward=relbias%3Ar%2C{%221%22%3A%22RI%3A10%22}|work=The New York Times|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n* St. Ann's Church \u2013 An unusual-looking high-rise in the East Village \u2013 the neighborhood's tallest \u2013 is a symbol of another conflict between the school's plans and residents' desires. On the site of the demolished St. Ann's Church on East 12th Street between Third and Fourth Avenues, the university planned to build a dorm and solicited community input on its plans. The community asked that the 240-foot-tall building be scaled back, only to find in 2006 that construction plans were moving ahead to build a 26-story dormitory. That building, Founder's Hall, now towers over one preserved wall of the former St. Ann's Church, the gray stone fa\u00e7ade facing E. 12th Street.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Anderson|first1=Lincoln|title=Conceding nothing, N.Y.U. starts building megadorm|url=http://thevillager.com/villager_170/concedingnothingnyu.html|work=[[The Villager (Manhattan)|The Villager]]|accessdate=8 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140820064150/http://thevillager.com/villager_170/concedingnothingnyu.html|archive-date=20 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* Provincetown Playhouse and Apartments \u2013 Located at 133-139 MacDougal Street, this four-story complex hosted performances of works by playwrights from Edna St. Vincent Millay to Eugene O'Neill to Sam Shepard in its playhouse, while artists and others found shelter in the apartments above. In 2008 the school proposed to demolish the entire building and rebuild a facility for the law school, as well as a new theater.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Amateau|first1=Albert|title=N.Y.U. would drop curtain on O'Neill's playhouse|url=http://thevillager.com/villager_260/nyuwoulddrop.html|work=[[The Villager (Manhattan)|The Villager]]|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> The same year, the New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation responded positively to GVSHP's request that the building be found eligible for listing on the State and National Registers of Historic Places. In the face of community opposition, NYU agreed to preserve just six percent of the old building: the walls containing the small theater in the southern corner of the building. However, during construction, behind construction barriers and invisible from the street, NYU secretly tore down parts of the walls they promised to preserve, a fact publicly revealed by GVSHP.<ref>{{cite web|title=Re: Failure to Maintain Commitments re:Provincetown Playhouse Theater Restoration|url=http://www.gvshp.org/_gvshp/preservation/ptown/doc/ltr-nyu-11-19-10.pdf|publisher=Greenwich Village Society for Historic Preservation|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>  \n* NYU 2031 \u2013 This ambitious plan for the university's expansion was met by wide resistance both among unaffiliated city residents, and among university faculty and staff.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Berger|first1=Joseph|title=N.Y.U.'s Plan for Expansion Draws Anger in Community|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/10/nyregion/nyu-expansion-plan-upsets-some-greenwich-village-neighbors.html?pagewanted=all|work=The New York Times|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref> Not only did community members consider the plan itself an abrogation of the \"Planning Principles\" that came out of the Community Task Force, but a new group formed called NYU Faculty Against the Sexton Plan (NYU FASP). When the city approved the 2031 plan, FASP, GVSHP and others filed suit to stop it. In January 2014, State Supreme Court Justice Donna Mills halted the plan based on illegal takings of parkland, but NYU appealed.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Bagli|first1=Charles|title=Judge Blocks Part of N.Y.U.'s Plan for Four Towers in Greenwich Village|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/01/08/nyregion/judge-blocks-part-of-nyus-plan-for-four-towers-in-greenwich-village.html|work=The New York Times|accessdate=8 September 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Recent construction===\nOver the last few years, NYU has developed a number of new facilities on and around its Washington Square campus.\n\nThe Kimmel Center for University Life, named for benefactors Helen and [[Martin Kimmel]], was built in 2003 to house the majority of the University's student services offices. The center also houses the Skirball Center for the Performing Arts, the Rosenthal Pavilion, the Eisner & Lubin Auditorium, and the Loeb Student Center. The Jack H. Skirball Center for the Performing Arts is a professionally operated and programmed 850-seat [[Proscenium|proscenium theater]]. Presentations there have included the Abbey Theater of Dublin's Playboy of the Western World, the world premiere of Mabou Mines Red Beads, a series of concerts by World Music Institute, and a series of superlative dance companies, including Lar Lubovitch and Bill T. Jones. The Skirball Center is the largest performing arts facility south of [[42nd Street (Manhattan)|42nd Street]].<ref>http://www.nyu.edu/kimmel/perf_arts.shtml The Skirball Center for the Performing Arts</ref>\n\nThe School of Law's Furman Hall, built in 2004, was named for NYU Law alumnus Jay Furman (JD '71). Rebuilt elements of two historic buildings were incorporated into the new facade, one of which was occupied by poet [[Edgar Allan Poe]].<ref>Albert Amateau. [http://www.thevillager.com/villager_37/nyuopensnew.html \"N.Y.U. opens new building for law school\".] ''The Villager''. Volume 73, Number 37, January 14\u20132, 2004</ref>\n\nIn 2005, NYU announced the development of a new life science facility on [[Waverly Place]]. The facility will accommodate laboratories and related academic space for the life sciences and will be the first NYU science building developed since the opening of Meyer Hall in 1971.<ref>Lincoln Anderson. \"N.Y.U. to use Waverly buildings for its new life sciences center\". ''The Villager''. Volume 74, Number 28, November 17\u201322, 2004 http://www.thevillager.com/villager_81/nyutousewaverly.html</ref>\n\nIn November 2005, NYU announced plans to build a 26-floor, {{convert|190000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} residence hall on 12th Street. The residence hall is expected to accommodate about 700 undergraduates and contain a host of other student facilities. It is to be the tallest building in the [[East Village, Manhattan|East Village]].<ref>[http://media.www.nyunews.com/media/storage/paper869/news/2005/11/08/NewscampusNews/New-Dorm.Coming.In.2009-2387197.shtml New dorm coming in 2009: 26-story residence hall to be built on 12th Street] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071013035314/http://media.www.nyunews.com/media/storage/paper869/news/2005/11/08/NewscampusNews/New-Dorm.Coming.In.2009-2387197.shtml# |date=2007-10-13 }}, ''NYU News'', November 8, 2005</ref> The plans have caused anger among East Village and other [[New York City]] residents, as the new building would be built over the old St. Ann's Church.<ref>[http://villagevoice.com/news/0610,lombardi,72426,2.html Not Subject to Review: As NYU plans towering dorm for 12th Street, East Village neighbors cry foul] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070626080717/http://www.villagevoice.com/news/0610,lombardi,72426,2.html# |date=2007-06-26 }}, ''[[The Village Voice]]'', March 7, 2006</ref> Following construction, the new residence hall was named [[Founders Hall (New York University)|Founders Hall]].\n\nA new $1.3 billion building will replace the [[Coles Sports and Recreation Center]] at 404 Lafayette Street formerly located on the site. The building, set to open in 2021, will include a gym, a swimming pool, three theaters and class rooms. It will be topped by two towers with faculty and student housing.<ref>http://asumag.com/facility-planning/new-york-university-details-plans-13-billion-building</ref>\n\n==Brooklyn campus==\n[[File:Wunsch Building.JPG|alt=|left|thumb|Wunsch Building, a former church]]\nThe [[New York University Tandon School of Engineering|Tandon School of Engineering]] is located in [[Downtown Brooklyn]]. It is centrally located in the [[MetroTech Center]] and is close to transportation routes and easily accessible from all parts of New York City and Long Island. The Brooklyn campus offers programs for undergraduates students as well as for graduate students, including those executive programs for students with related experience.\n\nThe engineering school played a leadership role in bringing about MetroTech Center, one of the largest urban university-corporate parks in the world and the largest in the United States. Today, the 16-acre (65,000 m\u00b2), $1 billion complex is home to the institute and several technology-dependent companies, including Securities Industry Automation Corporation (SIAC), New York City Police Department's 911 Center, New York City Fire Department Headquarters and the U.S. technology and operations functions of JPMorgan Chase. In 1998, a Marriott Hotel was built adjacent to MetroTech. MetroTech has proven to be a case study in effective university, corporate, government and private-developer cooperation. It has resulted in renewing an area that once was characterized more by urban decay.\n\nThe [[Wunsch Building]] which now houses the NYU Wasserman Center for Career Development's Brooklyn Office, dates back to 1847 and was the first independent black church in Brooklyn. It was also a stop on the Underground Railroad and has been designated a historic landmark since November 24, 1981.\n\nThe Bern Dibner Library of Science and Technology, opened in 1990, is the engineering school's library.  In addition, wireless networks allow users with notebook computers to access the library's electronic services from anywhere on campus.\n\nThe Brooklyn campus also houses the [[Center for Urban Science and Progress]] as well as several of [[Tisch School of the Arts]]<ref name=\"animationcareerreview.com\">http://www.animationcareerreview.com/articles/top-50-game-design-schools-and-colleges-us-%E2%80%93-2015</ref> and [[Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development]]'s degree programs.<ref>http://magnet.nyu.edu/</ref> The Brooklyn campus houses NYU's Game Center Open Library, which is the largest collection of games held by any university in the world.<ref name=\"animationcareerreview.com\"/> In 2014, [[NYU Langone Medical Center]] acquired a 125,000 square foot healthcare facility in Brooklyn.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Frost|first1=Mary|title=NYU Langone to take over LICH emergency department in Brooklyn on Friday|url=http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2014/10/29/nyu-langone-take-over-lich-emergency-department-brooklyn-friday|website=Brooklyn Daily Eagle|accessdate=April 4, 2016|date=October 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\nDesign and engineering work for the full renovation and fit-out of [[370 Jay Street]] in Brooklyn is underway. Construction began in February 2015,<ref>{{cite web|title=Construction; Current Projects: 370 Jay Street|url=https://www.nyu.edu/community/nyu-in-nyc/construction/current-projects/370-Jay-Street-project.html|publisher=[[New York University]]|accessdate=July 24, 2017}}</ref> and NYU started moving into the building in December 2017.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.metro.us/news/local-news/new-york/nyu-moves-tech-hub-long-empty-former-mta-headquarters|title=NYU moves tech hub into long-empty former MTA headquarters|last=Toussaint|first=Kristin|date=2017-12-13|work=Metro US|access-date=2017-12-15|language=en}}</ref> The 460,000-square-foot building, which NYU acquired in 2013, is adjacent to its Tandon School of Engineering.<ref name=\"nyu.edu\"/>\n\n==Medical campus==\nThe main NYU medical campus is situated at the East River waterfront at First Ave. between East 30th and [[34th Street (Manhattan)|34th Street]]s. The campus hosts the Medical School, Tisch Hospital, and the [[Rusk Institute of Rehabilitation Medicine]]. Other NYU Centers across the city include NYU Hospital for Joint Diseases and the Bellevue Hospital Center. NYU's Ehrenkranz School of Social Work manages branch campus programs in Westchester County at [[Manhattanville College]] and in [[Rockland County]] at [[St. Thomas Aquinas College]]. In Sterling Forest, near Tuxedo, New York, NYU has a research facility that contains several institutes, in particular the Nelson Institute of Environmental Medicine. The Midtown Center at 11 West 42nd Street and the [[Woolworth Building]] in the financial district are home to NYU's continuing education programs.\n\n===Recent construction===\n* Ronald O. Perelman Center for Emergency Services, completed in 2014.<ref>http://nyulangone.org/our-story/campus-transformation/building-the-ronald-o-perelman-center-for-emergency-services</ref>\n* Energy Building, completed in 2016.<ref>http://nyulangone.org/our-story/campus-transformation/building-the-energy-building</ref>\n* 16-story Science Building, will be completed in 2017.<ref name=\"ny.curbed.com\">http://ny.curbed.com/2016/7/7/12116632/nyu-langone-expansion-kips-bay</ref>\n* 21-story Helen L. and Martin S. Kimmel Pavilion, will be completed in 2018.<ref name=\"ny.curbed.com\"/>\n\n==Foreign facilities==\nNYU has an extensive study abroad program in which a good portion of the student body participates; hence, the school has earned the nickname \"Global U\".{{Cite quote|date=August 2017}} Unlike most other universities, NYU has its own international facilities in several countries. One noteworthy example is the {{convert|57|acre|m2|adj=on}} campus of NYU Florence at [[Villa La Pietra]] in Italy, bequeathed by the late Sir [[Harold Acton]] to NYU in 1994.<ref>[http://www.nyu.edu/nyutoday/archives/16/01/Stories/LaPietra.html NYU Today<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> NYU manages undergraduate academic year study abroad programs at [[NYU Florence]], [[NYU London]], [[NYU Paris]], NYU Prague, NYU Berlin, NYU Accra, NYU Madrid, [[NYU Shanghai]], NYU Buenos Aires, NYU Tel Aviv, [[NYU Abu Dhabi]], NYU Washington, DC, and NYU Sydney.\n\n==International houses on campus==\nNYU has several international houses to foster the study of international culture and languages. The international houses have their own classroom space, libraries, offices, and often host campus events. The NYU international houses are:\n* [[Casa Italiana Zerilli-Marim\u00f2]]\n* [[La Maison Fran\u00e7aise (New York University)|La Maison Fran\u00e7aise]]\n* Deutsches Haus<ref>[http://deutscheshaus.as.nyu.edu/page/home Deutsches Haus]</ref>\n* Glucksman Ireland House<ref>[http://www.irelandhouse.fas.nyu.edu Glucksman Ireland House]</ref>\n* King Juan Carlos I of Spain Center\n* Hagop Kevorkian Center<ref>[http://neareaststudies.as.nyu.edu/page/home Hagop Kevorkian Center]</ref>\n* Africa House\n* China House\n\nNYU was also the founding member of the [[League of World Universities]].\n\n==Residence halls==\n[[File:NYU Founders Hall St. Ann's Church.jpg|thumb|right|Founder's Hall]]\n{{Main|NYU residence halls}}\nWith 12,500 residents, NYU has the seventh largest university housing system in the U.S. and the largest among private schools.<ref>[http://www.housing.umich.edu/general/topten.html UM General Information<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070305034155/http://www.housing.umich.edu/general/topten.html |date=2007-03-05 }}</ref> Uniquely, many of NYU residence halls are converted apartment complexes or old hotels. Most freshman residence halls are in the Washington Square area. While nearly all the upper classmen dorms are in the Union Square area, a few of them are as far as the [[Financial District, Manhattan]]. Until the Spring 2005 semester, NYU used a lottery system to determine eligibility for residence hall preference. Under this system, a student received one point for every semester they had lived in campus housing. Freshmen are freed from the lottery system and are by tradition placed in the halls closest to the main campus area. Therefore, historically, most of the students who lived in dorms found off-campus were sophomores. However, beginning in the fall 2006 semester, sophomores received priority housing, giving them first choice of residence halls. The purpose of this initiative was to keep the sophomore class together in the [[Union Square, Manhattan|Union Square]] area. As a result, the junior class (class of 2008) and the senior class (class of 2007) never benefited from first choice as sophomores or seniors. The university operates its own transit system to transport its students, by bus or trolley, to campus. Undergraduate students are guaranteed housing during their enrollment at NYU.\n\nTwenty-two buildings are in NYU's undergraduate housing system in the United States. In general, NYU residence halls receive favorable ratings, and some are opulent. Many rooms are spacious and contain amenities considered rare for individual college residence hall rooms, such as kitchens and living rooms/common areas, one residence hall even has maid service. All residence halls are staffed by 24-hour security staff, contain multiple [[resident assistant]]s (RAs), and several halls contain faculty in residence. Unlike many other universities, NYU rooms all have their own bathrooms and thus no common bathrooms exist. Many residence halls have their own dining hall, and the university has meal choices to suit various diets. Almost all the residence halls have a [[laundry]] room that is open to resident students 24 hours a day.\n\nAll the residence halls are governed by the [[Residence hall association|Inter-Residence Hall Council]] (IRHC), an umbrella student council organization. Each hall elects student representatives to the IRHC, and those representatives meet with one another to form committees and vote on an executive board. The goal of this group is to create programs for university students and to act as a link to university administration. [[Hometalk]] ranked NYU's student residences third in the United States in its list of best college dorms.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.hometalk.com/6444015/most-impressive-dorms |title=Archived copy |access-date=2016-04-25 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160504063304/http://www.hometalk.com/6444015/most-impressive-dorms |archive-date=2016-05-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Recent acquisitions==\nSome of the recent acquisitions include, among others:\n\n*In 2010, NYU purchased a 125,000 square foot building. Full renovation of 60 [[Fifth Avenue]] (formerly the Forbes Building) is expected to commence in February 2015.<ref name=\"nyu.edu\">http://www.nyu.edu/about/news-publications/budget/capital-budget.html</ref> \n*In 2014, NYU bought a 151,000-square-foot building in [[NoHo, Manhattan]] for $157 million and renovated it.<ref>http://therealdeal.com/blog/2014/10/28/nyu-buys-noho-building-for-157m/</ref> \n*In 2014, NYU acquired a 125,000 square foot healthcare facility in [[Brooklyn]].<ref>http://www.brooklyneagle.com/articles/2014/10/29/nyu-langone-take-over-lich-emergency-department-brooklyn-friday</ref>\n*In 2016, NYU bought a 94-unit rental building near Gramercy Park for $87.5 million. NYU purchased the building on behalf of its NYU School of Medicine to \"provide housing primarily for trainees and staff, including house staff, post-docs, and researchers. NYU Langone Medical Center's Tisch Hospital is located a few blocks north of the property, with other NYU medical facilities also located nearby on Manhattan's East Side\".<ref>http://therealdeal.com/2016/03/08/nyu-acquires-gramercy-park-rental-from-benchmark-for-88m/</ref>\n*In 2016, NYU signed a 30-year agreement to take 390,000 square feet of space at 222 East 41st, including all 25 floors, the lobby, common areas and the parking garage.<ref>http://therealdeal.com/2016/04/28/nyu-langone-leases-entire-390k-sf-building-in-midtown-east/</ref>\n*In 2016, NYU acquired [[Winthrop University Hospital]].<ref>http://libn.com/2016/09/29/nyu-langone-winthrop-approve-merger/</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Ibid|date=March 2020}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{New York University}}\n\n{{Coord|40|43|46|N|73|59|47|W|display=title}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:New York University|Campus]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Manhattan|New York University Campus]]\n[[Category:Culture of Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Greenwich Village|New York University Campus]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Manhattan|New York University Campus]]\n", "name_user": "Andrewmoody71", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Campus_of_New_York_University"}
{"title_page": "Fashion Revolution", "text_new": "{{advert|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:Who Made My Clothes Protest.jpg|thumb|Protestors hold \"Who Made My Clothes\" signs]]\n'''Fashion Revolution''' is a not-for-profit global movement with teams in over 100 countries around the world.  Fashion Revolution campaigns for systemic reform of the [[fashion]] industry with a focus on the need for greater [[Transparency (trade)|transparency]] in the fashion [[supply chain]].  Fashion Revolution has designated the anniversary of the [[Rana Plaza]] disaster in [[Bangladesh]] as Fashion Revolution Day. In 2014-2018, millions of people around the world called on brands to answer the question Who Made My Clothes? The [[hashtag]] #WhoMadeMyClothes became the no.1 global trend on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Muzaffar |first=Zareen |date=27 April 2015 |title=2 Years Later, Bangladesh's Rana Plaza Debacle Continues to Resonate Globally |url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/04/2-years-later-bangladeshs-rana-plaza-debacle-continues-to-resonate-globally/ |magazine=The Diplomat}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dearden |first=Lizzie |date=24 April 2015 |title=Fashion Revolution Day: #whomademyclothes campaign remembers Rana Plaza disaster |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/fashion/news/fashion-revolution-day-whomademyclothes-campaign-remembers-rana-plaza-disaster-10201871.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Ayre |first=Josie |date=24 April 2015 |title=It's Fashion Revolution Day! Here's Why It's So Important To Know Where Our Clothes Are Made... |url=http://www.marieclaire.co.uk/news/549144/fashion-revolution-day-2015-carry-somers-interview.html |magazine=Marie Claire}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Fashion Revolution]] was founded in 2013 in response to the [[2013 Dhaka garment factory collapse|Rana Plaza]] disaster in Bangladesh by [[Carry Somers]] and Orsola de Castro.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Yardley|first=Jim|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/23/world/asia/report-on-bangladesh-building-collapse-finds-widespread-blame.html|title=Report on Deadly Factory Collapse in Bangladesh Finds Widespread Blame|date=2013-05-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Somers and de Castro both had experience in the fashion industry. For the previous 20 years, Somers\u2019s fashion brand Pachacuti had pioneered radical supply chain transparency and de Castro had launched and run the pioneering upcycling label From Somewhere from 1997 until 2014.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/about/|title=ABOUT|website=Fashion Revolution|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Fashion Revolution was designed as a platform for academics, designers, writers, retailers, and business leaders to encourage people to take action in the fashion industry.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> The organization is funded by private foundations, institutional grants, commercial organizations, and donations from individuals. Somers and de Castro launched the #WhoMadeMyClothes hashtag in 2013.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite news|last=Blanchard|first=Tamsin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/commentisfree/2019/apr/22/who-made-my-clothes-stand-up-for-workers-rights-with-fashion-revolution-week|title=Who Made My Clothes? Stand up for workers' rights with Fashion Revolution Week {{!}} Tamsin Blanchard|date=2019-04-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, What Are You Wearing Day was incorporated into Fashion Revolution Day. observed on April 24th, International What Are You Wearing Day encourages people to be free in their fashion ensembles and post images of themselves on social media. The hashtag #WhatAreYouWearing trended as people expressed their fashion freedoms with other likeminded people.\n\n==Fashion Revolution Day / Fashion Revolution Week==\nFashion Revolution Day takes place annually on 24 April, the anniversary of the [[2013 Savar building collapse|2013 Rana Plaza building collapse]] when 1133 died and over 2500 were injured. In 2016, it expanded into Fashion Revolution Week. Fashion Revolution day was also created to highlight the current climate emergency. Awareness of the exploitation of supply chain workers has also been highlighted on the Fashion Revolution day. The movement's goal is to change the way clothes are sourced, produced, and purchased. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/|title=Home|website=Fashion Revolution|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\nThe first Fashion Revolution Day took place on 24 April 2014. Fashion Revolution's hashtag #insideout was the no. 1 global trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfam.org.uk/education/education-blog/2015/03/fashion-revolution-day |title=Fashion Revolution Day 2015 |website=Oxfam |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407162113/http://www.oxfam.org.uk/education/education-blog/2015/03/fashion-revolution-day |archive-date=7 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=The Guardian |first=Stephanie Hepburn |date=14 April 2015 |title=Can a hashtag change the fashion industry? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/sustainable-fashion-blog/2015/apr/14/can-a-hashtag-change-the-fashion-industry |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nThe second Fashion Revolution Day took place on 24 April 2015. The global reach from online news and broadcast media was 16.5 billion and 63 million people from across 76 countries made the hashtag #WhoMadeMyClothes the number one trend on Twitter<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bkaccelerator.com/is-social-media-traceabilitys-new-superman/ |title=Is Social Media Traceability's New Superman? |date=29 July 2015 |website=Brooklyn Fashion + Design Accelerator}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://stylebubble.co.uk/style_bubble/2015/05/grappling-with-the-true-cost.html |title=Grappling with the True Cost |website=Style Bubble |type=Blog}}</ref> The [[YouTube]] video ''The 2 Euro T-Shirt - A Social Experiment'' had over 6.5 million views and won a [[Cannes Lions International Festival of Creativity|Cannes Lions]] award.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Ketchum, Fashion Revolution and BBDO Group Germany Win Bronze PR Lion at Cannes Lions International Festival of Creativity |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ketchum-fashion-revolution-and-bbdo-group-germany-win-bronze-pr-lion-at-cannes-lions-international-festival-of-creativity-300104161.html |agency=PR Newswire}}</ref>\n\nIn its third year, Fashion Revolution activities took place over a week, from 18\u201324 April 2016. This first Fashion Revolution Week began with Fashion Question Time at the UK [[Houses of Parliament]].<ref name=\"marycreagh.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.marycreagh.com/fashion_question_time_in_parliament |title=Fashion Question Time in Parliament |website=Mary Creagh MP |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160501074349/http://www.marycreagh.com/fashion_question_time_in_parliament |archive-date=1 May 2016}}</ref> and the launch of the first edition of the Fashion Transparency Index, which scored 40 of the biggest global fashion companies on the information they disclose to stakeholders and the public about social and environmental issues across their supply chains.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/FR_FashionTransparencyIndex.pdf |title=Fashion Transparency Index |website=Fashion Revolution}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ethicalconsumer.org/fashion-clothing |title=Fashion and Clothing |date=27 March 2018 |website=Ethical Consumer |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/fashion-transparency-index_uk_5714b1c7e4b0f22f0219cbd0 |title=The High Street And Designer Brands Working Towards Sustainable Fashion |date=18 April 2016 |website=HuffPost |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref> 70,000 people around the world asked brands #whomademyclothes with 156 million impressions of the hashtag on social media. [[G-Star Raw]], [[American Apparel]], [[Fat Face]], [[Boden (clothing)|Boden]], [[Massimo Dutti]], [[Zara (retailer)|Zara]], and [[Warehouse (clothing)|Warehouse]] were among more than 1200 fashion brands and retailers that responded with photographs of their workers saying #imadeyourclothes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sourcingjournalonline.com/1000-brands-retailers-respond-fashion-revolution-challenge/ |title=Fashion Revolution Challenge Ignites Industry-Wide Responses |date=2016-07-25}}</ref>  Fashion Revolution achieved online media reach in April 2016 of 22 billion.<ref>http://fashionrevolution.org/about/2016-impact/{{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref> Social Experiment] was ranked no. 7 in the top global PR campaigns of the year at the Global Sabre Awards ceremony.<ref name=\"fox19.com\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.fox19.com/story/33501533/ketchum-and-its-clients-win-two-global-sabre-awards |title=Ketchum and its Clients Win Two Global SABRE Awards |agency=Frankly |access-date=2016-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104002500/http://www.fox19.com/story/33501533/ketchum-and-its-clients-win-two-global-sabre-awards |archive-date=2016-11-04 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ketchum-and-its-clients-win-two-global-sabre-awards-300353106.html|title=Ketchum and its Clients Win Two Global SABRE Awards|website=www.prnewswire.com}}</ref> The video has received over 7.5 million views.\n\nIn 2016's Fashion Revolution Week, events took place in over 90 countries around the world. Over 70,000 people around the world asked brands #whomademyclothes with 156 million impressions of the hashtag on social media. [[G-Star Raw]], [[American Apparel]], [[Fat Face]], [[Boden (clothing)|Boden]], [[Massimo Dutti]], [[Zara (retailer)|Zara]] and [[Warehouse (clothing)|Warehouse]] were among more than 1200 fashion brands and retailers that responded with photographs of their workers saying #imadeyourclothes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sourcingjournal.com/topics/labor/1000-brands-retailers-respond-fashion-revolution-challenge-50001/ |title=Fashion Revolution Challenge Ignites Industry-Wide Responses |first=Genevieve |last=Scarano |date=25 July 2016 |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>  Fashion Revolution achieved online media reach in April 2016 of 22 billion.<ref name=\"Home\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/ |title=Home |website=Fashion Revolution |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/fashion-revolution-transparency-index_uk_57cedaa6e4b09f5b5e37d4fd |title=These Fashion Brands Responded To Call For Supply Chain Transparency |date=6 September 2016 |website=HuffPost |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 October 2016, Fashion Revolution's ''\u20ac2 video, A Social Experiment'' was ranked no. 7 in the top global PR campaigns of the year at the Global Sabre Awards ceremony.<ref name=\"fox19.com\"/><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ketchum-and-its-clients-win-two-global-sabre-awards-300353106.html |title=Ketchum and its Clients Win Two Global SABRE Awards |last=Ketchum |agency=PR Newswire |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref> The video has received over 7.5 million views.\n\nIn its fourth year, Fashion Revolution Week took place from 24\u201330 April 2017. On Fashion Revolution Day, the second edition of the Fashion Transparency Index was launched, a review of 100 of the biggest global fashion brands and retailers ranked according to how much they disclose about their social and environmental policies, practices and impact.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://issuu.com/fashionrevolution/docs/fr_fashiontransparencyindex2017 |title=Fashion Transparency Index 2017 |website=Issuu  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/video/2017/04/25/no-fashion-brand-is-fully-transparent-re?videoId=371549837&videoChannel=5 |title=No fashion brand is fully transparent - report |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://spendmatters.com/2017/05/02/fashion-transparency-index-2017-released-favorite-brands-rank/ |title=Fashion Transparency Index 2017 Released: How Do Your Favorite Brands Rank? |date=2 May 2017 |website=Spend Matters |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref> 66,000 people attended around 1000 Fashion Revolution events and there were 533 million impressions of social media posts using one of Fashion Revolution's hashtags during April and over 2000 brands and producer groups responded, answering #imadeyourclothes.<ref name=\"Home\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/two-million-people-supported-fashion-revolution-week |title=Two million people supported Fashion Revolution Week |website=voice-online.co.uk |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn its fifth year, Fashion Revolution Week took place from 23\u201329 April 2018 <ref>{{cite news |last=The Guardian |first=Tamsin Blanchard |date=24 April 2018 |title=Fashion Revolution Week: seven ways to get involved |url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2018/apr/24/fashion-revolution-week-seven-ways-to-get-involved |newspaper=[[Guardian News|The Guardian]]}}</ref> when over 1000 Fashion Revolution events were held around the world, including Fashion Open Studio and Fashion Question Time at the Houses of Parliament. In April, the third edition of the Fashion Transparency Index was launched, ranking 150 brands on how much they disclose about their policies, practices, procedures and social and environmental impact.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dazed Digital |first=Morgane Nyfeler |date=24 April 2018 |title=Are fashion brands actually making progress at becoming ethical? |url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/fashion/article/39855/1/are-fashion-brands-becoming-ethical-fashion-revolution-transparency-index-2018 |newspaper=[[Dazed Digital|Dazed]]}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\nDuring Fashion Revolution Week, hundreds of events take place around the world). Fashion Revolution has also organized high-level roundtable events on [[ethics]], [[sustainability]], and transparency in the fashion industry.\n\n12 May 2014: Roundtable Debate in UK [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sustainable-fashion.com/blog/roundtable-debate/ |title=Roundtable debate |date=19 May 2014 |website=Sustainable Fashion}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iosh.co.uk/News/Fatal-factory-collapse-must-be-wake-up-call-to-improve-health-and-safety-of-supply-chain-workers.aspx |title=Fatal factory collapse must be wake-up call to improve health and safety of supply chain workers |website=Institution of Occupational Safety and Health}}</ref>\n\n26 February 2015: Fashion Question Time in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|UK House of Commons]] with [[Mary Creagh]] MP, [[Lily Cole]], Jenny Holdcroft, policy director of [[IndustriALL Global Union]] Catarina Midby, Global Head of Sustainable Communications, [[H&M]] Dilys Williams, Head, Centre for Sustainable Fashion, and [[Anas Sarwar]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fashionrevolution.org/fashion-question-time-at-the-houses-of-parliament/ |title=Fashion Question Time at the Houses of Parliament |website=Fashion Revolution |access-date=2015-07-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712124744/http://fashionrevolution.org/fashion-question-time-at-the-houses-of-parliament/ |archive-date=2015-07-12 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.impossible.com/lily-speaks-at-fashion-question-time-at-the-houses-of-parliament/ |title=Lily speaks at Fashion Question Time at the Houses of Parliament |website=[[impossible.com]]}}</ref>\n\n29 June 2015: Ethical Fashion 2020: a New Vision for Transparency in UK [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Whale |first=Sebastian |date=6 July 2015 |title=IOSH discussion: Towards Ethical Fashion 2020 |url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/features/450361/iosh-discussion-towards-ethical-fashion-2020.thtml |magazine=[[Total Politics]]}}</ref>\n\n2 December 2015: EU roundtable and launch of White Paper on transparency 'It's Time for a Fashion Revolution' in Brussels.<ref name=\"Home\"/>\n\n18 April 2016: Fashion Question Time at the Houses of Parliament.<ref name=\"marycreagh.com\"/><ref name=\"Home\"/>\n\nDuring Fashion Revolution Week 2017, 1000 events took place around the country including Fashion Question Time at the Houses of Parliament on 24 April<ref>{{cite web |url=http://francescorner.com/2017/04/fashion-question-time/ |title=Fashion Question Time |website=Frances Corner |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044727/http://francescorner.com/2017/04/fashion-question-time/ |archive-date=1 December 2017}}</ref> and the launch of Open Studios, a week-long series of events across London, New York, Athens, Prato in Italy, LA and Jakarta.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/04/18/fashion-revolution-announce-their-first-open-studios-as-part-of-whomademyclothes-campaign-6581932/ |title=Fashion Revolution announce first open studios as part of their new campaign |date=18 April 2017 |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== #WhoMadeMyClothes Hashtag Movement ==\nThe #WhoMadeMyClothes hashtag was launched in 2013 by Fashion Revolution co-founders, Carry Somers and Orsola de Castro.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> It became the number 1 global trend on Twitter. By 2018, the hashtag received 99.6 million impressions on Twitter and 170 000 posts were shared on Twitter and Instagram containing at least one of Fashion Revolution's hashtags.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/oliviapinnock/2018/05/04/the-best-answers-to-whomademyclothes-this-fashion-revolution-week/|title=The Best Answers To #WhoMadeMyClothes This Fashion Revolution Week|last=Pinnock|first=Olivia|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The goal of the hashtag was to bring awareness to consumers about the brands that they purchase from and raise awareness for the humanitarian and ethical issues in fast fashion. Garment workers in factories responded to the movement by participating with the hashtag #IMadeYourClothes.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe movement began in [[England]] and spread through social media. On Twitter, 31.82% of the tweets with #WhoMadeMyClothes were posted by users from the United Kingdom. The top 5 countries with the highest search activity and Twitter posts for #WhoMadeMyClothes were the United Kingdom, the United States, Germany, Canada, and France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hashtagify.me/hashtag/whomademyclothes|title=#whomademyclothes: Popularity, Trend, Related Hashtags|website=Hashtagify|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Celebrities including Emma Watson, Kelly Slater, and Fernanda Paes Leme used the hashtag on Twitter to support the issue.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/2018-impact/|title=2018 Impact|website=Fashion Revolution|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nThe movement also utilized YouTube to spread awareness. To promote the hashtag in 2015, Fashion Revolution released a video titled \u201cThe 2 Euro T-Shirt - A Social Experiment\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.red-dot.org/about-red-dot/magazine/2-euro-t-shirt/|title=Award-winning design and its makers: \"The 2 Euro T-Shirt \u2013 A Social Experiment\"|last=Dot|first=Red|website=www.red-dot.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The video showed a vending machine selling t-shirts for 2 Euros. When people went to purchase the shirt, a video played describing the working conditions in which the shirt was made. By the end, people chose to donate to the cause of increasing supply chain transparency instead of buying the t-shirt. The video has over 7.9 million views. Their 2018 campaign film uploaded on April 22nd, 2018 was awarded the Best Green Fashion Film award at the Fashion Film Festival Milano and has over 54,000 views to date.<ref>{{Citation|title=Who Made My Clothes?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XTnFfa0qHIM|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nWith the hashtag #WhoMadeMyClothes as the channel for the movement, there was an increase in the general awareness of the reality behind the garment manufacturing processes. With increased awareness, global fashion brands have started to increase transparency. The 2018 Transparency Index allowed fashion brands the opportunity to change and justify their supply chains. As of June 2018, 172 brands across 68 countries have revealed more information about their supply chains than in previous years. In response to the hashtag, #WhoMadeMyClothes, more than 3,838 global brands took to social media to respond with real information about their suppliers and workers.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==== Criticism ====\nDespite the public attention brought by Fashion Revolution, people remain skeptical of the movement\u2019s actions and consequences. In an article written by [[The Guardian]], Ruth Stokes, author of The Armchair Activist\u2019s Handbook, says that meaningful change in the fashion industry can start with a Fashion Revolution Day hashtag campaign, but must go beyond it.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hepburn|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/sustainable-fashion-blog/2015/apr/14/can-a-hashtag-change-the-fashion-industry|title=Can a hashtag change the fashion industry?|date=2015-04-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Fashion Revolution publications & podcasts==\nFashion Revolution publishes online a variety of campaign assets, posters, brand guidelines, postcard and letter writing templates, and action kits (for citizens, brands, wholesalers, retailers, distributors, farmers, producers and factories).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/resources/free-downloads/ |title=FREE DOWNLOADS |website=Fashion Revolution  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> In addition, it has published the following:\n\n''How to be a Fashion Revolutionary''( 2015) which is 'full of inspiration and ideas about how you can use your voice and your power to transform the fashion industry as we know it'. This is available in English,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/HowToBeAFashionRevolutionary.pdf |title=How to Be a Fashion Revolutionary (English) |website= |url-status=live }}</ref> Spanish<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/HowToBeAFashionRevolutionary_Spanish.pdf |title=C\u00d3MO SER UN REVOLUCIONARIO DE LA MODA (Spanish) |website= |url-status=live }}</ref> and Portuguese<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/How-to-be-a-Fash-Revolutionary_portuguese.pdf |title=COMO SER UM REVOLUCION\u00c1RIO DA MODA |website= |url-status=live }}</ref> and was published as part of a touring Fashion Revolution exhibition and film screenings at UK universities.\n\n''It's Time for a Fashion Revolution'' (2015) sets out the need for more transparency across the fashion industry, from seed to waste. This is available in English<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/FashRev_Whitepaper_Dec2015_screen.pdf |title=It's Time for a Fashion Revolution |website=Fashion Revolution |url-status=live }}</ref> and Spanish.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/FashRev_Whitepaper_Dec2015_Spanish.pdf |title=It's Time for a Fashion Revolution |website=Fashion Revolution |url-status=live |language=es}}</ref>\n\n''Fashion Transparency Index'' (2016 & 2017) ranks the biggest global fashion companies (40 in 2016, 100 in 2017) according to their level of transparency based on a questionnaire and publicly available information about supply chain issues. The 2016 Index - published in collaboration with Ethical Consumer - is available in English and Spanish,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ethicalconsumer.org/fashion-clothing |title=Fashion and Clothing |date=2018-03-27 |website=Ethical Consumer  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/FashionTransparencyIndex2016_ES_Light.pdf |title=\u00cdNDICE DE TRANSPARENCIA DE LA MODA |website= |url-status=live }}</ref> and the 2017 Index is available in English, Spanish and Portuguese.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://issuu.com/fashionrevolution/docs/fr_fashiontransparencyindex2017/1 |title=Fashion Transparency Index 2017 |website=issuu |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://issuu.com/fashionrevolution/docs/fr_fashiontransparencyindex2017_esp/1 |title=\u00cdndice de Transparencia de la Moda |website=issuu |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://issuu.com/fashionrevolution/docs/fr_indice_2017/1 |title=\u00cdndice de Transpar\u00eancia da Moda 2017 |website=issuu |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\n''Money, Fashion, Power'' (2017) is a zine which comprising 72-pages of poetry, illustration, photography, graphic design and editorial exploring the hidden stories behind clothing, pricing, and the purchasing power of consumers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/resources/fanzine/ |title=Buy Fanzine #001: Money Fashion Power |website= |url-status=live }}</ref> Collectible hard copies could be purchased and a free digital version was published online.\n\n''Loved Clothes Last'' (2017) is a zine comprising 124 pages of poetry, illustration, photography, infographics, and packed with articles, tips and interviews exploring the issue of waste and mass-consumption in the fashion industry, and hopes to inspire you to buy less, care more, and know how to make the clothes you love last for longer. Collectible hard copies could be purchased and a free digital version was published online.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/resources/fanzine2/ |title=Buy Fanzine #002: LOVED CLOTHES LAST |website=Fashion Revolution  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\n''Fashion Revolution Podcast'' series (2017) comprises three 27 minute recordings in which international fashion journalist Tamsin Blanchard speaks to researchers, supply chain experts, garment workers, politicians and activists about the intersection of sustainability, ethics, and transparency in the fashion industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/resources/listen-to-the-fashion-revolution-podcast/ |title=LISTEN TO THE PODCAST |website=Fashion Revolution  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\n''Garment Worker Diaries'' (2017\u201318) is a project by Microfinance Opportunities in collaboration with Fashion Revolution which, over 12 months, visited the same set of garment workers in Bangladesh, India, and Cambodia to 'learn what they could earn and buy, how they spend their time each day, and what their working conditions are like'.<ref name=\"workerdiaries.org\">{{cite web |url=https://workerdiaries.org/ |title=Garment Worker Diaries |website=workerdiaries.org |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref> Its (interactive) research reports and podcast are written to 'advocate for changes in consumer and corporate behaviors and policy changes that improve the living and working conditions of garment workers everywhere'.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://workerdiaries.org/garment-worker-diaries-reports/ |title=Reports : Garment Worker Diaries |website=workerdiaries.org |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref name=\"workerdiaries.org\"/>\n\n== Haulternative campaign ==\nThe #Haulternative campaign, in conjunction with the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', features fashion [[vloggers]] filming themselves doing an alternative fashion haul.<ref>{{cite news |last=Blanchard |first=Tamsin |date=24 April 2015 |title=Best of the high street's collections |url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/article/TMG11536174/Fashion-Revolution-Day-Youtube-haulers-get-ethical-with-haulternative-campaign.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150421043015/http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/article/TMG11536174/Fashion-Revolution-Day-Youtube-haulers-get-ethical-with-haulternative-campaign.html |archive-date=21 April 2015}}</ref> Haulers who participated included [[CutiePieMarzia]],<ref>{{Citation |title=HAULTERNATIVE SWAP WITH CUTIEPIEMARZIA |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Kbr-pnXD4A  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> [[Noodlerella]], Bip Ling, [[Grav3yardgirl]], and Shameless Maya<ref>{{Citation |title=DIY: Summer Crop Top #Haulternative |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8m_5Wo17-fM  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> with combined views of 2 million on [[YouTube]].\n\n== Schools, colleges and universities ==\nIn 2014, Fashion Revolution published a quiz and an education pack for school, college and university teachers, and students. These were freely available online.\n\nIn 2015, a new quiz and separate education worksheets were produced for primary schools (7\u201311 years), secondary schools (11\u201316 years), further education colleges (16\u201318 years) and universities (18+).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://europa.eu/eyd2015/en/fashion-revolution/posts/be-curious-find-out-do-something |title=Be curious. Find out. Do something. |last1=Cook |first1=Ian |website=European Year for Development |accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref> These were published in English and translated into Spanish, Finnish and other languages by Country Coordination teams.\n\nTo encourage students to be curious, dig deeper, and more involved on #whomademyclothes, these worksheets continue to be developed and now include :\n* 'Introduction to Fashion Revolution PowerPoint' (Primary - Universities)\n* 'Design a Fashion Revolution Poster' (Primary - Universities),\n* 'What can I find out about my clothes?' (Primary),\n* 'Where are my clothes made?' (Primary),\n* 'Write to the person who made my clothes' (Primary),\n* 'Research my clothes and write to the brand' (Secondary - FE), \n* 'Fashion Revolution Trump Card Game' (Secondary - Universities),\n* 'What my jeans say about the garment industry' (Secondary - Universities)\n* 'Take a selfie and send it to the brand' (Secondary - University), \n* 'Fashion Revolution Annual Quiz' (Primary - Universities) and\n* 'Tableau Vivant' (Universities).\n\nIn July 2015, a collection of social media postings showing how teachers and students got involved the Fashion Revolution was published on [[Pinterest]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pinterest.com/fashrevglobal/education/ |title=Education |website=Pinterest  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> along with a 'who made my clothes?' film library,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pinterest.com/fashrevglobal/film-library/ |title=81 Best Film Library images {{!}} Film, Fashion, Ethical shopping |website=Pinterest  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> and a collection of 'imaginative ways in which the work of artists, activists and others can be used to inspire and engage people in the Fashion Revolution'.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pinterest.com/fashrevglobal/do-something/ |title=116 Best Do something images in 2020 {{!}} Something to do, Fashion, Revolution |website=Pinterest  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> These continue to be updated.\n\nIn August 2016, three sessions were organized at the Annual Conference of the [[Royal Geographical Society|Royal Geographical Society (with Institute of British Geographers)]] conference in London with academic and activist speakers talking to the theme of \"Scholar activism and the Fashion Revolution: \u2018who made my clothes?\u2019\" Session one focused on connecting producers and consumers,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conference.rgs.org/AC2016/157 |title=AC2016 - Scholar activism and the Fashion Revolution: 'who made my clothes?' (1): connecting producers and consumers |website=conference.rgs.org |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> session two on slow sustainable fashion in practice<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conference.rgs.org/AC2016/191 |title=AC2016 - Scholar activism and the Fashion Revolution: 'who made my clothes?' (1): connecting producers and consumers |website=conference.rgs.org |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> and session three on engaging publics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conference.rgs.org/AC2016/225 |title=AC2016 - Scholar activism and the Fashion Revolution: 'who made my clothes?' (1): connecting producers and consumers |website=conference.rgs.org |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\nIn June\u2013July 2017, a free 3-week online course called 'Who Made My Clothes' was created in collaboration with the [[University of Exeter]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.futurelearn.com/courses/who-made-my-clothes |title=Fashion Revolution: Who Made My Clothes? - Online Course |last=FutureLearn |website=FutureLearn  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> Run by and featuring members of Fashion Revolution's Global Coordination Team - Ian Cook, Orsola de Castro, Sarah Ditty and Joss Whipple - the course included over 8,000 learners worldwide, and covered topics such as the pay and conditions of people working in the global garment industry. The course will run again in June\u2013July 2018.\n\n== Criticisms ==\nIn 2016, various fashion brands criticized Fashion Revolution by questioning the methods that the organization and the website [[Ethical Consumer]] used for the Transparency Index. The index assesses the level of transparency and support for workers\u2019 rights of various fashion brands by looking at the information released by the company and by distributing various questionnaires. In an article by [[Women's Wear Daily|Women\u2019s Wear Daily]], the founder of Fashion Revolution responded to the criticisms by explaining how the index was not meant to be a way to audit the companies but rather a way to assess the accessibility of the information regarding the supply chain processes of their product to the customers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-scoops/fashion-revolution-criticism-transparency-index-chanel-fendi-sustainability-10421031/|title=Fashion Revolution Responds to Criticism From Brands on Its Transparency Index|last=Theodosi|first=Natalie|last2=Theodosi|first2=Natalie|date=2016-04-29|website=WWD|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://fashionrevolution.org/ Fashion Revolution website]\n\n{{Fashion}}\n\n[[Category:Fashion organizations]]\n[[Category:Clothing controversies]]\n[[Category:Workers' rights organizations]]\n[[Category:Business ethics organizations]]\n[[Category:Social responsibility organizations]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organisations based in England]]\n", "text_old": "{{advert|date=May 2019}}\n[[File:Who Made My Clothes Protest.jpg|thumb|Protestors hold \"Who Made My Clothes\" signs]]\n'''Fashion Revolution''' is a not-for-profit global movement with teams in over 100 countries around the world.  Fashion Revolution campaigns for systemic reform of the [[fashion]] industry with a focus on the need for greater [[Transparency (trade)|transparency]] in the fashion [[supply chain]].  Fashion Revolution has designated the anniversary of the [[Rana Plaza]] disaster in [[Bangladesh]] as Fashion Revolution Day. In 2014-2018, millions of people around the world called on brands to answer the question Who Made My Clothes? The [[hashtag]] #WhoMadeMyClothes became the no.1 global trend on [[Twitter]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Muzaffar |first=Zareen |date=27 April 2015 |title=2 Years Later, Bangladesh's Rana Plaza Debacle Continues to Resonate Globally |url=http://thediplomat.com/2015/04/2-years-later-bangladeshs-rana-plaza-debacle-continues-to-resonate-globally/ |magazine=The Diplomat}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Dearden |first=Lizzie |date=24 April 2015 |title=Fashion Revolution Day: #whomademyclothes campaign remembers Rana Plaza disaster |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/life-style/fashion/news/fashion-revolution-day-whomademyclothes-campaign-remembers-rana-plaza-disaster-10201871.html |newspaper=The Independent |location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine |last=Ayre |first=Josie |date=24 April 2015 |title=It's Fashion Revolution Day! Here's Why It's So Important To Know Where Our Clothes Are Made... |url=http://www.marieclaire.co.uk/news/549144/fashion-revolution-day-2015-carry-somers-interview.html |magazine=Marie Claire}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Fashion Revolution]] was founded in 2013 in response to the [[2013 Dhaka garment factory collapse|Rana Plaza]] disaster in Bangladesh by [[Carry Somers]] and Orsola de Castro.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Yardley|first=Jim|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2013/05/23/world/asia/report-on-bangladesh-building-collapse-finds-widespread-blame.html|title=Report on Deadly Factory Collapse in Bangladesh Finds Widespread Blame|date=2013-05-22|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Somers and de Castro both had experience in the fashion industry. For the previous 20 years, Somers\u2019s fashion brand Pachacuti had pioneered radical supply chain transparency and de Castro had launched and run the pioneering upcycling label From Somewhere from 1997 until 2014.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/about/|title=ABOUT|website=Fashion Revolution|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Fashion Revolution was designed as a platform for academics, designers, writers, retailers, and business leaders to encourage people to take action in the fashion industry.<ref name=\"auto1\"/> The organization is funded by private foundations, institutional grants, commercial organizations, and donations from individuals. Somers and de Castro launched the #WhoMadeMyClothes hashtag in 2013.<ref name=\"auto3\">{{Cite news|last=Blanchard|first=Tamsin|url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/commentisfree/2019/apr/22/who-made-my-clothes-stand-up-for-workers-rights-with-fashion-revolution-week|title=Who Made My Clothes? Stand up for workers' rights with Fashion Revolution Week {{!}} Tamsin Blanchard|date=2019-04-22|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Fashion Revolution Day / Fashion Revolution Week==\nFashion Revolution Day takes place annually on 24 April, the anniversary of the [[2013 Savar building collapse|2013 Rana Plaza building collapse]] when 1133 died and over 2500 were injured. In 2016, it expanded into Fashion Revolution Week. Fashion Revolution day was also created to highlight the current climate emergency. Awareness of the exploitation of supply chain workers has also been highlighted on the Fashion Revolution day. The movement's goal is to change the way clothes are sourced, produced, and purchased. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/|title=Home|website=Fashion Revolution|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\nThe first Fashion Revolution Day took place on 24 April 2014. Fashion Revolution's hashtag #insideout was the no. 1 global trend on Twitter.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.oxfam.org.uk/education/education-blog/2015/03/fashion-revolution-day |title=Fashion Revolution Day 2015 |website=Oxfam |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150407162113/http://www.oxfam.org.uk/education/education-blog/2015/03/fashion-revolution-day |archive-date=7 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=The Guardian |first=Stephanie Hepburn |date=14 April 2015 |title=Can a hashtag change the fashion industry? |url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/sustainable-fashion-blog/2015/apr/14/can-a-hashtag-change-the-fashion-industry |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nThe second Fashion Revolution Day took place on 24 April 2015. The global reach from online news and broadcast media was 16.5 billion and 63 million people from across 76 countries made the hashtag #WhoMadeMyClothes the number one trend on Twitter<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bkaccelerator.com/is-social-media-traceabilitys-new-superman/ |title=Is Social Media Traceability's New Superman? |date=29 July 2015 |website=Brooklyn Fashion + Design Accelerator}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://stylebubble.co.uk/style_bubble/2015/05/grappling-with-the-true-cost.html |title=Grappling with the True Cost |website=Style Bubble |type=Blog}}</ref> The [[YouTube]] video ''The 2 Euro T-Shirt - A Social Experiment'' had over 6.5 million views and won a [[Cannes Lions International Festival of Creativity|Cannes Lions]] award.<ref>{{cite press release |title=Ketchum, Fashion Revolution and BBDO Group Germany Win Bronze PR Lion at Cannes Lions International Festival of Creativity |url=http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ketchum-fashion-revolution-and-bbdo-group-germany-win-bronze-pr-lion-at-cannes-lions-international-festival-of-creativity-300104161.html |agency=PR Newswire}}</ref>\n\nIn its third year, Fashion Revolution activities took place over a week, from 18\u201324 April 2016. This first Fashion Revolution Week began with Fashion Question Time at the UK [[Houses of Parliament]].<ref name=\"marycreagh.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.marycreagh.com/fashion_question_time_in_parliament |title=Fashion Question Time in Parliament |website=Mary Creagh MP |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160501074349/http://www.marycreagh.com/fashion_question_time_in_parliament |archive-date=1 May 2016}}</ref> and the launch of the first edition of the Fashion Transparency Index, which scored 40 of the biggest global fashion companies on the information they disclose to stakeholders and the public about social and environmental issues across their supply chains.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/FR_FashionTransparencyIndex.pdf |title=Fashion Transparency Index |website=Fashion Revolution}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ethicalconsumer.org/fashion-clothing |title=Fashion and Clothing |date=27 March 2018 |website=Ethical Consumer |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/fashion-transparency-index_uk_5714b1c7e4b0f22f0219cbd0 |title=The High Street And Designer Brands Working Towards Sustainable Fashion |date=18 April 2016 |website=HuffPost |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref> 70,000 people around the world asked brands #whomademyclothes with 156 million impressions of the hashtag on social media. [[G-Star Raw]], [[American Apparel]], [[Fat Face]], [[Boden (clothing)|Boden]], [[Massimo Dutti]], [[Zara (retailer)|Zara]], and [[Warehouse (clothing)|Warehouse]] were among more than 1200 fashion brands and retailers that responded with photographs of their workers saying #imadeyourclothes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sourcingjournalonline.com/1000-brands-retailers-respond-fashion-revolution-challenge/ |title=Fashion Revolution Challenge Ignites Industry-Wide Responses |date=2016-07-25}}</ref>  Fashion Revolution achieved online media reach in April 2016 of 22 billion.<ref>http://fashionrevolution.org/about/2016-impact/{{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref> Social Experiment] was ranked no. 7 in the top global PR campaigns of the year at the Global Sabre Awards ceremony.<ref name=\"fox19.com\">{{cite press release |url=http://www.fox19.com/story/33501533/ketchum-and-its-clients-win-two-global-sabre-awards |title=Ketchum and its Clients Win Two Global SABRE Awards |agency=Frankly |access-date=2016-11-02 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161104002500/http://www.fox19.com/story/33501533/ketchum-and-its-clients-win-two-global-sabre-awards |archive-date=2016-11-04 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ketchum-and-its-clients-win-two-global-sabre-awards-300353106.html|title=Ketchum and its Clients Win Two Global SABRE Awards|website=www.prnewswire.com}}</ref> The video has received over 7.5 million views.\n\nIn 2016's Fashion Revolution Week, events took place in over 90 countries around the world. Over 70,000 people around the world asked brands #whomademyclothes with 156 million impressions of the hashtag on social media. [[G-Star Raw]], [[American Apparel]], [[Fat Face]], [[Boden (clothing)|Boden]], [[Massimo Dutti]], [[Zara (retailer)|Zara]] and [[Warehouse (clothing)|Warehouse]] were among more than 1200 fashion brands and retailers that responded with photographs of their workers saying #imadeyourclothes.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://sourcingjournal.com/topics/labor/1000-brands-retailers-respond-fashion-revolution-challenge-50001/ |title=Fashion Revolution Challenge Ignites Industry-Wide Responses |first=Genevieve |last=Scarano |date=25 July 2016 |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>  Fashion Revolution achieved online media reach in April 2016 of 22 billion.<ref name=\"Home\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/ |title=Home |website=Fashion Revolution |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.co.uk/entry/fashion-revolution-transparency-index_uk_57cedaa6e4b09f5b5e37d4fd |title=These Fashion Brands Responded To Call For Supply Chain Transparency |date=6 September 2016 |website=HuffPost |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 October 2016, Fashion Revolution's ''\u20ac2 video, A Social Experiment'' was ranked no. 7 in the top global PR campaigns of the year at the Global Sabre Awards ceremony.<ref name=\"fox19.com\"/><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/ketchum-and-its-clients-win-two-global-sabre-awards-300353106.html |title=Ketchum and its Clients Win Two Global SABRE Awards |last=Ketchum |agency=PR Newswire |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref> The video has received over 7.5 million views.\n\nIn its fourth year, Fashion Revolution Week took place from 24\u201330 April 2017. On Fashion Revolution Day, the second edition of the Fashion Transparency Index was launched, a review of 100 of the biggest global fashion brands and retailers ranked according to how much they disclose about their social and environmental policies, practices and impact.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://issuu.com/fashionrevolution/docs/fr_fashiontransparencyindex2017 |title=Fashion Transparency Index 2017 |website=Issuu  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/video/2017/04/25/no-fashion-brand-is-fully-transparent-re?videoId=371549837&videoChannel=5 |title=No fashion brand is fully transparent - report |accessdate=16 May 2019 |work=Reuters}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://spendmatters.com/2017/05/02/fashion-transparency-index-2017-released-favorite-brands-rank/ |title=Fashion Transparency Index 2017 Released: How Do Your Favorite Brands Rank? |date=2 May 2017 |website=Spend Matters |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref> 66,000 people attended around 1000 Fashion Revolution events and there were 533 million impressions of social media posts using one of Fashion Revolution's hashtags during April and over 2000 brands and producer groups responded, answering #imadeyourclothes.<ref name=\"Home\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/two-million-people-supported-fashion-revolution-week |title=Two million people supported Fashion Revolution Week |website=voice-online.co.uk |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn its fifth year, Fashion Revolution Week took place from 23\u201329 April 2018 <ref>{{cite news |last=The Guardian |first=Tamsin Blanchard |date=24 April 2018 |title=Fashion Revolution Week: seven ways to get involved |url=https://www.theguardian.com/fashion/2018/apr/24/fashion-revolution-week-seven-ways-to-get-involved |newspaper=[[Guardian News|The Guardian]]}}</ref> when over 1000 Fashion Revolution events were held around the world, including Fashion Open Studio and Fashion Question Time at the Houses of Parliament. In April, the third edition of the Fashion Transparency Index was launched, ranking 150 brands on how much they disclose about their policies, practices, procedures and social and environmental impact.<ref>{{cite news |last=Dazed Digital |first=Morgane Nyfeler |date=24 April 2018 |title=Are fashion brands actually making progress at becoming ethical? |url=https://www.dazeddigital.com/fashion/article/39855/1/are-fashion-brands-becoming-ethical-fashion-revolution-transparency-index-2018 |newspaper=[[Dazed Digital|Dazed]]}}</ref>\n\n==Events==\nDuring Fashion Revolution Week, hundreds of events take place around the world). Fashion Revolution has also organized high-level roundtable events on [[ethics]], [[sustainability]], and transparency in the fashion industry.\n\n12 May 2014: Roundtable Debate in UK [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sustainable-fashion.com/blog/roundtable-debate/ |title=Roundtable debate |date=19 May 2014 |website=Sustainable Fashion}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iosh.co.uk/News/Fatal-factory-collapse-must-be-wake-up-call-to-improve-health-and-safety-of-supply-chain-workers.aspx |title=Fatal factory collapse must be wake-up call to improve health and safety of supply chain workers |website=Institution of Occupational Safety and Health}}</ref>\n\n26 February 2015: Fashion Question Time in the [[House of Commons of the United Kingdom|UK House of Commons]] with [[Mary Creagh]] MP, [[Lily Cole]], Jenny Holdcroft, policy director of [[IndustriALL Global Union]] Catarina Midby, Global Head of Sustainable Communications, [[H&M]] Dilys Williams, Head, Centre for Sustainable Fashion, and [[Anas Sarwar]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fashionrevolution.org/fashion-question-time-at-the-houses-of-parliament/ |title=Fashion Question Time at the Houses of Parliament |website=Fashion Revolution |access-date=2015-07-31 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150712124744/http://fashionrevolution.org/fashion-question-time-at-the-houses-of-parliament/ |archive-date=2015-07-12 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.impossible.com/lily-speaks-at-fashion-question-time-at-the-houses-of-parliament/ |title=Lily speaks at Fashion Question Time at the Houses of Parliament |website=[[impossible.com]]}}</ref>\n\n29 June 2015: Ethical Fashion 2020: a New Vision for Transparency in UK [[House of Lords]].<ref>{{cite magazine |last=Whale |first=Sebastian |date=6 July 2015 |title=IOSH discussion: Towards Ethical Fashion 2020 |url=http://www.totalpolitics.com/features/450361/iosh-discussion-towards-ethical-fashion-2020.thtml |magazine=[[Total Politics]]}}</ref>\n\n2 December 2015: EU roundtable and launch of White Paper on transparency 'It's Time for a Fashion Revolution' in Brussels.<ref name=\"Home\"/>\n\n18 April 2016: Fashion Question Time at the Houses of Parliament.<ref name=\"marycreagh.com\"/><ref name=\"Home\"/>\n\nDuring Fashion Revolution Week 2017, 1000 events took place around the country including Fashion Question Time at the Houses of Parliament on 24 April<ref>{{cite web |url=http://francescorner.com/2017/04/fashion-question-time/ |title=Fashion Question Time |website=Frances Corner |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044727/http://francescorner.com/2017/04/fashion-question-time/ |archive-date=1 December 2017}}</ref> and the launch of Open Studios, a week-long series of events across London, New York, Athens, Prato in Italy, LA and Jakarta.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://metro.co.uk/2017/04/18/fashion-revolution-announce-their-first-open-studios-as-part-of-whomademyclothes-campaign-6581932/ |title=Fashion Revolution announce first open studios as part of their new campaign |date=18 April 2017 |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n== #WhoMadeMyClothes Hashtag Movement ==\nThe #WhoMadeMyClothes hashtag was launched in 2013 by Fashion Revolution co-founders, Carry Somers and Orsola de Castro.<ref name=\"auto3\"/> It became the number 1 global trend on Twitter. By 2018, the hashtag received 99.6 million impressions on Twitter and 170 000 posts were shared on Twitter and Instagram containing at least one of Fashion Revolution's hashtags.<ref name=\"auto2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/oliviapinnock/2018/05/04/the-best-answers-to-whomademyclothes-this-fashion-revolution-week/|title=The Best Answers To #WhoMadeMyClothes This Fashion Revolution Week|last=Pinnock|first=Olivia|website=Forbes|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The goal of the hashtag was to bring awareness to consumers about the brands that they purchase from and raise awareness for the humanitarian and ethical issues in fast fashion. Garment workers in factories responded to the movement by participating with the hashtag #IMadeYourClothes.<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\nThe movement began in [[England]] and spread through social media. On Twitter, 31.82% of the tweets with #WhoMadeMyClothes were posted by users from the United Kingdom. The top 5 countries with the highest search activity and Twitter posts for #WhoMadeMyClothes were the United Kingdom, the United States, Germany, Canada, and France.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hashtagify.me/hashtag/whomademyclothes|title=#whomademyclothes: Popularity, Trend, Related Hashtags|website=Hashtagify|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Celebrities including Emma Watson, Kelly Slater, and Fernanda Paes Leme used the hashtag on Twitter to support the issue.<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/2018-impact/|title=2018 Impact|website=Fashion Revolution|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nThe movement also utilized YouTube to spread awareness. To promote the hashtag in 2015, Fashion Revolution released a video titled \u201cThe 2 Euro T-Shirt - A Social Experiment\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.red-dot.org/about-red-dot/magazine/2-euro-t-shirt/|title=Award-winning design and its makers: \"The 2 Euro T-Shirt \u2013 A Social Experiment\"|last=Dot|first=Red|website=www.red-dot.org|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> The video showed a vending machine selling t-shirts for 2 Euros. When people went to purchase the shirt, a video played describing the working conditions in which the shirt was made. By the end, people chose to donate to the cause of increasing supply chain transparency instead of buying the t-shirt. The video has over 7.9 million views. Their 2018 campaign film uploaded on April 22nd, 2018 was awarded the Best Green Fashion Film award at the Fashion Film Festival Milano and has over 54,000 views to date.<ref>{{Citation|title=Who Made My Clothes?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XTnFfa0qHIM|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\nWith the hashtag #WhoMadeMyClothes as the channel for the movement, there was an increase in the general awareness of the reality behind the garment manufacturing processes. With increased awareness, global fashion brands have started to increase transparency. The 2018 Transparency Index allowed fashion brands the opportunity to change and justify their supply chains. As of June 2018, 172 brands across 68 countries have revealed more information about their supply chains than in previous years. In response to the hashtag, #WhoMadeMyClothes, more than 3,838 global brands took to social media to respond with real information about their suppliers and workers.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==== Criticism ====\nDespite the public attention brought by Fashion Revolution, people remain skeptical of the movement\u2019s actions and consequences. In an article written by [[The Guardian]], Ruth Stokes, author of The Armchair Activist\u2019s Handbook, says that meaningful change in the fashion industry can start with a Fashion Revolution Day hashtag campaign, but must go beyond it.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Hepburn|first=Stephanie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sustainable-business/sustainable-fashion-blog/2015/apr/14/can-a-hashtag-change-the-fashion-industry|title=Can a hashtag change the fashion industry?|date=2015-04-14|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n==Fashion Revolution publications & podcasts==\nFashion Revolution publishes online a variety of campaign assets, posters, brand guidelines, postcard and letter writing templates, and action kits (for citizens, brands, wholesalers, retailers, distributors, farmers, producers and factories).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/resources/free-downloads/ |title=FREE DOWNLOADS |website=Fashion Revolution  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> In addition, it has published the following:\n\n''How to be a Fashion Revolutionary''( 2015) which is 'full of inspiration and ideas about how you can use your voice and your power to transform the fashion industry as we know it'. This is available in English,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/HowToBeAFashionRevolutionary.pdf |title=How to Be a Fashion Revolutionary (English) |website= |url-status=live }}</ref> Spanish<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/HowToBeAFashionRevolutionary_Spanish.pdf |title=C\u00d3MO SER UN REVOLUCIONARIO DE LA MODA (Spanish) |website= |url-status=live }}</ref> and Portuguese<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/How-to-be-a-Fash-Revolutionary_portuguese.pdf |title=COMO SER UM REVOLUCION\u00c1RIO DA MODA |website= |url-status=live }}</ref> and was published as part of a touring Fashion Revolution exhibition and film screenings at UK universities.\n\n''It's Time for a Fashion Revolution'' (2015) sets out the need for more transparency across the fashion industry, from seed to waste. This is available in English<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/11/FashRev_Whitepaper_Dec2015_screen.pdf |title=It's Time for a Fashion Revolution |website=Fashion Revolution |url-status=live }}</ref> and Spanish.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/04/FashRev_Whitepaper_Dec2015_Spanish.pdf |title=It's Time for a Fashion Revolution |website=Fashion Revolution |url-status=live |language=es}}</ref>\n\n''Fashion Transparency Index'' (2016 & 2017) ranks the biggest global fashion companies (40 in 2016, 100 in 2017) according to their level of transparency based on a questionnaire and publicly available information about supply chain issues. The 2016 Index - published in collaboration with Ethical Consumer - is available in English and Spanish,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ethicalconsumer.org/fashion-clothing |title=Fashion and Clothing |date=2018-03-27 |website=Ethical Consumer  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/03/FashionTransparencyIndex2016_ES_Light.pdf |title=\u00cdNDICE DE TRANSPARENCIA DE LA MODA |website= |url-status=live }}</ref> and the 2017 Index is available in English, Spanish and Portuguese.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://issuu.com/fashionrevolution/docs/fr_fashiontransparencyindex2017/1 |title=Fashion Transparency Index 2017 |website=issuu |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://issuu.com/fashionrevolution/docs/fr_fashiontransparencyindex2017_esp/1 |title=\u00cdndice de Transparencia de la Moda |website=issuu |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://issuu.com/fashionrevolution/docs/fr_indice_2017/1 |title=\u00cdndice de Transpar\u00eancia da Moda 2017 |website=issuu |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\n''Money, Fashion, Power'' (2017) is a zine which comprising 72-pages of poetry, illustration, photography, graphic design and editorial exploring the hidden stories behind clothing, pricing, and the purchasing power of consumers.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/resources/fanzine/ |title=Buy Fanzine #001: Money Fashion Power |website= |url-status=live }}</ref> Collectible hard copies could be purchased and a free digital version was published online.\n\n''Loved Clothes Last'' (2017) is a zine comprising 124 pages of poetry, illustration, photography, infographics, and packed with articles, tips and interviews exploring the issue of waste and mass-consumption in the fashion industry, and hopes to inspire you to buy less, care more, and know how to make the clothes you love last for longer. Collectible hard copies could be purchased and a free digital version was published online.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/resources/fanzine2/ |title=Buy Fanzine #002: LOVED CLOTHES LAST |website=Fashion Revolution  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\n''Fashion Revolution Podcast'' series (2017) comprises three 27 minute recordings in which international fashion journalist Tamsin Blanchard speaks to researchers, supply chain experts, garment workers, politicians and activists about the intersection of sustainability, ethics, and transparency in the fashion industry.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fashionrevolution.org/resources/listen-to-the-fashion-revolution-podcast/ |title=LISTEN TO THE PODCAST |website=Fashion Revolution  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\n''Garment Worker Diaries'' (2017\u201318) is a project by Microfinance Opportunities in collaboration with Fashion Revolution which, over 12 months, visited the same set of garment workers in Bangladesh, India, and Cambodia to 'learn what they could earn and buy, how they spend their time each day, and what their working conditions are like'.<ref name=\"workerdiaries.org\">{{cite web |url=https://workerdiaries.org/ |title=Garment Worker Diaries |website=workerdiaries.org |accessdate=16 May 2019}}</ref> Its (interactive) research reports and podcast are written to 'advocate for changes in consumer and corporate behaviors and policy changes that improve the living and working conditions of garment workers everywhere'.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://workerdiaries.org/garment-worker-diaries-reports/ |title=Reports : Garment Worker Diaries |website=workerdiaries.org |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref><ref name=\"workerdiaries.org\"/>\n\n== Haulternative campaign ==\nThe #Haulternative campaign, in conjunction with the ''[[Daily Telegraph]]'', features fashion [[vloggers]] filming themselves doing an alternative fashion haul.<ref>{{cite news |last=Blanchard |first=Tamsin |date=24 April 2015 |title=Best of the high street's collections |url=http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/article/TMG11536174/Fashion-Revolution-Day-Youtube-haulers-get-ethical-with-haulternative-campaign.html |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph |location=London |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150421043015/http://fashion.telegraph.co.uk/article/TMG11536174/Fashion-Revolution-Day-Youtube-haulers-get-ethical-with-haulternative-campaign.html |archive-date=21 April 2015}}</ref> Haulers who participated included [[CutiePieMarzia]],<ref>{{Citation |title=HAULTERNATIVE SWAP WITH CUTIEPIEMARZIA |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3Kbr-pnXD4A  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> [[Noodlerella]], Bip Ling, [[Grav3yardgirl]], and Shameless Maya<ref>{{Citation |title=DIY: Summer Crop Top #Haulternative |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=8m_5Wo17-fM  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> with combined views of 2 million on [[YouTube]].\n\n== Schools, colleges and universities ==\nIn 2014, Fashion Revolution published a quiz and an education pack for school, college and university teachers, and students. These were freely available online.\n\nIn 2015, a new quiz and separate education worksheets were produced for primary schools (7\u201311 years), secondary schools (11\u201316 years), further education colleges (16\u201318 years) and universities (18+).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://europa.eu/eyd2015/en/fashion-revolution/posts/be-curious-find-out-do-something |title=Be curious. Find out. Do something. |last1=Cook |first1=Ian |website=European Year for Development |accessdate=9 August 2016}}</ref> These were published in English and translated into Spanish, Finnish and other languages by Country Coordination teams.\n\nTo encourage students to be curious, dig deeper, and more involved on #whomademyclothes, these worksheets continue to be developed and now include :\n* 'Introduction to Fashion Revolution PowerPoint' (Primary - Universities)\n* 'Design a Fashion Revolution Poster' (Primary - Universities),\n* 'What can I find out about my clothes?' (Primary),\n* 'Where are my clothes made?' (Primary),\n* 'Write to the person who made my clothes' (Primary),\n* 'Research my clothes and write to the brand' (Secondary - FE), \n* 'Fashion Revolution Trump Card Game' (Secondary - Universities),\n* 'What my jeans say about the garment industry' (Secondary - Universities)\n* 'Take a selfie and send it to the brand' (Secondary - University), \n* 'Fashion Revolution Annual Quiz' (Primary - Universities) and\n* 'Tableau Vivant' (Universities).\n\nIn July 2015, a collection of social media postings showing how teachers and students got involved the Fashion Revolution was published on [[Pinterest]],<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pinterest.com/fashrevglobal/education/ |title=Education |website=Pinterest  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> along with a 'who made my clothes?' film library,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pinterest.com/fashrevglobal/film-library/ |title=81 Best Film Library images {{!}} Film, Fashion, Ethical shopping |website=Pinterest  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> and a collection of 'imaginative ways in which the work of artists, activists and others can be used to inspire and engage people in the Fashion Revolution'.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pinterest.com/fashrevglobal/do-something/ |title=116 Best Do something images in 2020 {{!}} Something to do, Fashion, Revolution |website=Pinterest  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> These continue to be updated.\n\nIn August 2016, three sessions were organized at the Annual Conference of the [[Royal Geographical Society|Royal Geographical Society (with Institute of British Geographers)]] conference in London with academic and activist speakers talking to the theme of \"Scholar activism and the Fashion Revolution: \u2018who made my clothes?\u2019\" Session one focused on connecting producers and consumers,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conference.rgs.org/AC2016/157 |title=AC2016 - Scholar activism and the Fashion Revolution: 'who made my clothes?' (1): connecting producers and consumers |website=conference.rgs.org |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> session two on slow sustainable fashion in practice<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conference.rgs.org/AC2016/191 |title=AC2016 - Scholar activism and the Fashion Revolution: 'who made my clothes?' (1): connecting producers and consumers |website=conference.rgs.org |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> and session three on engaging publics.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://conference.rgs.org/AC2016/225 |title=AC2016 - Scholar activism and the Fashion Revolution: 'who made my clothes?' (1): connecting producers and consumers |website=conference.rgs.org |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\nIn June\u2013July 2017, a free 3-week online course called 'Who Made My Clothes' was created in collaboration with the [[University of Exeter]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.futurelearn.com/courses/who-made-my-clothes |title=Fashion Revolution: Who Made My Clothes? - Online Course |last=FutureLearn |website=FutureLearn  |access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref> Run by and featuring members of Fashion Revolution's Global Coordination Team - Ian Cook, Orsola de Castro, Sarah Ditty and Joss Whipple - the course included over 8,000 learners worldwide, and covered topics such as the pay and conditions of people working in the global garment industry. The course will run again in June\u2013July 2018.\n\n== Criticisms ==\nIn 2016, various fashion brands criticized Fashion Revolution by questioning the methods that the organization and the website [[Ethical Consumer]] used for the Transparency Index. The index assesses the level of transparency and support for workers\u2019 rights of various fashion brands by looking at the information released by the company and by distributing various questionnaires. In an article by [[Women's Wear Daily|Women\u2019s Wear Daily]], the founder of Fashion Revolution responded to the criticisms by explaining how the index was not meant to be a way to audit the companies but rather a way to assess the accessibility of the information regarding the supply chain processes of their product to the customers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://wwd.com/fashion-news/fashion-scoops/fashion-revolution-criticism-transparency-index-chanel-fendi-sustainability-10421031/|title=Fashion Revolution Responds to Criticism From Brands on Its Transparency Index|last=Theodosi|first=Natalie|last2=Theodosi|first2=Natalie|date=2016-04-29|website=WWD|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://fashionrevolution.org/ Fashion Revolution website]\n\n{{Fashion}}\n\n[[Category:Fashion organizations]]\n[[Category:Clothing controversies]]\n[[Category:Workers' rights organizations]]\n[[Category:Business ethics organizations]]\n[[Category:Social responsibility organizations]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organisations based in England]]\n", "name_user": "ArtsPatron1", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fashion_Revolution"}
{"title_page": "There's a sucker born every minute", "text_new": "\"'''There's a sucker born every minute'''\" is a phrase closely associated with [[P. T. Barnum]], an American showman of the mid-19th century, although there is no evidence that he actually said it. Early examples of its use are found among gamblers and [[Confidence trick|confidence men]].And he died some time as one of the owners of the CARDIFF giant\n\n==Attribution to Barnum==\nBarnum's biographer Arthur H. Saxon tried to track down when Barnum had uttered this phrase but was unable to verify it. According to Saxon, \"There's no contemporary account of it, or even any suggestion that the word 'sucker' was used in the derogatory sense in his day. Barnum was just not the type to disparage his patrons.\"<ref>Brooks, Andree (October 3, 1982). [https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/03/nyregion/debunking-the-myth-of-pt-barnum.html \"Debunking the Myth of P. T. Barnum\"]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved April 27, 2014.</ref>\n\n[[File:PT Barnum by Eisenmann, 1885.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Photo of P. T. Barnum by [[Charles Eisenmann]]]]\n\nSome sources claim that it is most likely from famous [[con-man]] Joseph (\"Paper Collar Joe\") Bessimer,<ref>{{cite book|title=P. T. Barnum: the Legend and the Man|first=A. H.|last=Saxon|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=1989}}</ref> and other sources say that it was actually uttered by David Hannum in reference to Barnum's part in the [[Cardiff Giant]] hoax.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.historyreference.org/library/refbarnum.html |title=HistoryReference.org: P. T. Barnum Never Did Say \"There's a Sucker Born Every Minute\" |access-date=2017-02-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306050828/http://www.historyreference.org/library/refbarnum.html |archive-date=2017-03-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Hannum was exhibiting the \"original\" giant and had unsuccessfully sued Barnum for exhibiting a copy and claiming that it was the original. Crowds continued to pay to see Barnum's exhibit, even after both it and the original had been proven to be fakes.{{citation needed|date = March 2020}}\n\nAnother source credits late 1860s Chicago saloon owner Michael Cassius McDonald as the originator of the aphorism. According to the book ''Gem of the Prairie: Chicago Underworld'' (1940) by [[Herbert Asbury]], McDonald was equipping his gambling house known as ''The Store'' when his partner expressed concern over the large number of roulette wheels and [[Faro (card game)|faro]] tables being installed and their ability to get enough players. McDonald then allegedly said, \"Don't worry about that, there's a sucker born every minute.\"{{Page needed|date=April 2014}}\n\n==History==\nEarly uses of the phrase refer to it as a catch-phrase among gamblers. In an 1879 discussion of gambling in Chicago, an \"old-timer\" is quoted as saying, \"[G]oodness knows how they live, it\u2019s mighty hard times with the most of them; in the season they make a bit on base ball, or on the races, and then, you know, 'there\u2019s a sucker born every minute', and rigid city legislation drives the hard-up gambler, who would be a decent one of the kind, to turn skin-dealer and sure-thing player.\"<ref> {{cite news|title=Gambling in Chicago |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4980045/early_use_of_theres_a_sucker_born/|newspaper=The Inter-Ocean|date=January 2, 1879|page=5|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 18, 2016}} {{Open access}}</ref> The use of quotation marks indicates that it must already have been an established catch-phrase.\n\nThe phrase appears in print in the 1885 biography of [[confidence trick|confidence man]] [[Hungry Joe]], ''The Life of Hungry Joe, King of the Bunco Men''.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Ricky |last=Jay |authorlink=Ricky Jay |title=Grifters, Bunco Artists & Flimflam Men |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |volume=19 |issue=02 |date=February 2011 |page=90}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Life of Hungry Joe, King of the Bunco Men |url=http://iiif.lib.harvard.edu/manifests/view/drs:32287114$24i|publisher=Frank Tousey |location=New York |year=1885 |page=22|oclc=78310948}}</ref> \n\nIn a slightly different form, the phrase shows up in the January 1806 ''[[European Magazine]]'': \"It was the observation of one of the [[Jews|tribe of Levi]], to whom some person had expressed his astonishment at his being able to sell his damaged and worthless commodities, 'That there vash von fool born every minute.'\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=Essay on False Genius|journal=The European Magazine and London Review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dccPAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA26|date=January 1806}}</ref>\n\nAccording to David W. Maurer, writing in ''The Big Con'' (1940),<ref>{{Cite book |last=Maurer |first=David W. |origyear=1940 |year=1999 |title=The Big Con: The Story of the Confidence Man and the Confidence Game (reprinted)  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxbbV5x66usC&lpg=PP1&dq=%22the%20big%20con%22&pg=PA297#v=onepage&q=knock&f=false|location=New York |publisher=Bobbs Merrill / Anchor Books |isbn=0-385-49538-2}}</ref> there was a similar saying amongst con men: \"There's a mark born every minute, and one to trim 'em and one to knock 'em.\"  Here \"trim\" means to steal from, and \"knock\" means to persuade away from a scam.  The meaning is that there is no shortage of new victims, nor of con men, nor of honest men.\n\nIn the 1930 [[John Dos Passos]] novel ''[[The 42nd Parallel]]'', the quotation is attributed to [[Mark Twain]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Barnum effect]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wikiquote-inline|P. T. Barnum}}\n\n{{Barnum}}\n\n[[Category:English phrases]]\n", "text_old": "\"'''There's a sucker born every minute'''\" is a phrase closely associated with [[P. T. Barnum]], an American showman of the mid-19th century, although there is no evidence that he actually said it. Early examples of its use are found among gamblers and [[Confidence trick|confidence men]].\n\n==Attribution to Barnum==\nBarnum's biographer Arthur H. Saxon tried to track down when Barnum had uttered this phrase but was unable to verify it. According to Saxon, \"There's no contemporary account of it, or even any suggestion that the word 'sucker' was used in the derogatory sense in his day. Barnum was just not the type to disparage his patrons.\"<ref>Brooks, Andree (October 3, 1982). [https://www.nytimes.com/1982/10/03/nyregion/debunking-the-myth-of-pt-barnum.html \"Debunking the Myth of P. T. Barnum\"]. ''The New York Times''. Retrieved April 27, 2014.</ref>\n\n[[File:PT Barnum by Eisenmann, 1885.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Photo of P. T. Barnum by [[Charles Eisenmann]]]]\n\nSome sources claim that it is most likely from famous [[con-man]] Joseph (\"Paper Collar Joe\") Bessimer,<ref>{{cite book|title=P. T. Barnum: the Legend and the Man|first=A. H.|last=Saxon|publisher=Columbia University Press|year=1989}}</ref> and other sources say that it was actually uttered by David Hannum in reference to Barnum's part in the [[Cardiff Giant]] hoax.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.historyreference.org/library/refbarnum.html |title=HistoryReference.org: P. T. Barnum Never Did Say \"There's a Sucker Born Every Minute\" |access-date=2017-02-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170306050828/http://www.historyreference.org/library/refbarnum.html |archive-date=2017-03-06 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Hannum was exhibiting the \"original\" giant and had unsuccessfully sued Barnum for exhibiting a copy and claiming that it was the original. Crowds continued to pay to see Barnum's exhibit, even after both it and the original had been proven to be fakes.{{citation needed|date = March 2020}}\n\nAnother source credits late 1860s Chicago saloon owner Michael Cassius McDonald as the originator of the aphorism. According to the book ''Gem of the Prairie: Chicago Underworld'' (1940) by [[Herbert Asbury]], McDonald was equipping his gambling house known as ''The Store'' when his partner expressed concern over the large number of roulette wheels and [[Faro (card game)|faro]] tables being installed and their ability to get enough players. McDonald then allegedly said, \"Don't worry about that, there's a sucker born every minute.\"{{Page needed|date=April 2014}}\n\n==History==\nEarly uses of the phrase refer to it as a catch-phrase among gamblers. In an 1879 discussion of gambling in Chicago, an \"old-timer\" is quoted as saying, \"[G]oodness knows how they live, it\u2019s mighty hard times with the most of them; in the season they make a bit on base ball, or on the races, and then, you know, 'there\u2019s a sucker born every minute', and rigid city legislation drives the hard-up gambler, who would be a decent one of the kind, to turn skin-dealer and sure-thing player.\"<ref> {{cite news|title=Gambling in Chicago |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/4980045/early_use_of_theres_a_sucker_born/|newspaper=The Inter-Ocean|date=January 2, 1879|page=5|via = [[Newspapers.com]]|accessdate = April 18, 2016}} {{Open access}}</ref> The use of quotation marks indicates that it must already have been an established catch-phrase.\n\nThe phrase appears in print in the 1885 biography of [[confidence trick|confidence man]] [[Hungry Joe]], ''The Life of Hungry Joe, King of the Bunco Men''.<ref>{{cite journal |first=Ricky |last=Jay |authorlink=Ricky Jay |title=Grifters, Bunco Artists & Flimflam Men |journal=[[Wired (magazine)|Wired]] |volume=19 |issue=02 |date=February 2011 |page=90}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=The Life of Hungry Joe, King of the Bunco Men |url=http://iiif.lib.harvard.edu/manifests/view/drs:32287114$24i|publisher=Frank Tousey |location=New York |year=1885 |page=22|oclc=78310948}}</ref> \n\nIn a slightly different form, the phrase shows up in the January 1806 ''[[European Magazine]]'': \"It was the observation of one of the [[Jews|tribe of Levi]], to whom some person had expressed his astonishment at his being able to sell his damaged and worthless commodities, 'That there vash von fool born every minute.'\"<ref>{{cite journal|title=Essay on False Genius|journal=The European Magazine and London Review|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dccPAAAAQAAJ&pg=PA26|date=January 1806}}</ref>\n\nAccording to David W. Maurer, writing in ''The Big Con'' (1940),<ref>{{Cite book |last=Maurer |first=David W. |origyear=1940 |year=1999 |title=The Big Con: The Story of the Confidence Man and the Confidence Game (reprinted)  |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jxbbV5x66usC&lpg=PP1&dq=%22the%20big%20con%22&pg=PA297#v=onepage&q=knock&f=false|location=New York |publisher=Bobbs Merrill / Anchor Books |isbn=0-385-49538-2}}</ref> there was a similar saying amongst con men: \"There's a mark born every minute, and one to trim 'em and one to knock 'em.\"  Here \"trim\" means to steal from, and \"knock\" means to persuade away from a scam.  The meaning is that there is no shortage of new victims, nor of con men, nor of honest men.\n\nIn the 1930 [[John Dos Passos]] novel ''[[The 42nd Parallel]]'', the quotation is attributed to [[Mark Twain]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Barnum effect]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{wikiquote-inline|P. T. Barnum}}\n\n{{Barnum}}\n\n[[Category:English phrases]]\n", "name_user": "216.137.246.108", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/There%27s_a_sucker_born_every_minute"}
